{"title_page": "Max Wirth (cyclist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Swiss cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Max Wirth\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| fullname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1930|9|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Zurich]], Switzerland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Max Wirth''' (born 9 September 1930) is a Swiss cyclist. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|4,000 metres team pursuit]] event at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/wi/max-wirth-1.html |title=Max Wirth Olympic Results |accessdate=28 December 2012 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wirth, Max}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Z\u00fcrich]]\n{{Switzerland-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swiss cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Max Wirth\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| fullname      = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1930|9|9|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Zurich]], Switzerland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height        = \n| weight        = \n| currentteam   = \n| discipline    = \n| role          = \n| ridertype     = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1  = \n| proyears1     = \n| proteam1      = \n| majorwins     = \n}}\n\n'''Max Wirth''' (born 9 September 1930) is a Swiss cyclist. He competed in the [[Cycling at the 1952 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's team pursuit|4,000 metres team pursuit]] event at the [[1952 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/wi/max-wirth-1.html |title=Max Wirth Olympic Results |accessdate=2012-12-28 |work=sports-reference.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wirth, Max}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swiss male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Olympic cyclists of Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Cyclists at the 1952 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Z\u00fcrich]]\n{{Switzerland-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Wirth_(cyclist)"}
{"title_page": "The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:The Lumiere brothers center for photography.jpg|thumb|The facade of The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography]]\n'''The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography''' is a private exhibition organization located in the former chocolate factory and acting art cluster Red October in Moscow.\n\nSince its foundation in 2010, the center aims to explore and promote Russian and foreign photography, support emerging Russian artists and explore beyond the medium. A private collection of [[Natalia Grigorieva-Litvinskaya|Natalia]] and Eduard Litvinsky laid the foundation for the center's collection.\n\nWorks from the Center's collection were shown at the Fotofest 2012 Biennal, triennial Bergen Assembly in 2013, [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]], museum and exhibition association [[Manege]], [[Jewish Museum and Tolerance Center]], [[Tretyakov Gallery]] in Moscow.\n\nThe center's exhibitions were shown at the [[Russian Museum|State Russian Museum]] and [[Erarta]] in St-Petersburg, Krasnoyarsk museum center, Cherepovets museum association, Kazan city hall, Ekaterinburg Museum of Fine Arts, and [[Heydar Aliyev Center]] in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]].\n\n==Exhibition programme ==\nFor the past 19 years the gallery has amassed a vast collection of prints featuring chef d\u2019oeuvres by renowned Soviet and the World famous artists: [[Alexander Rodchenko]], [[Antanas Sutkus]], Yakov Khalip, Vladimir Lagrange, [[Arnold Newman]], [[Wynn Bullock]], [[Ruth Orkin]], [[Elliott Erwitt]], [[Steve Schapiro]], [[Guy Bourdin]], [[Vivian Maier]], [[Sabine Weiss]], [[Harry Benson]], [[Sheila Metzner]], [[Miles Aldridge]].\n\nThe center's exhibition programme aims to explore and present photography to a wider audience. The program has been built around the center\u2019s collection and collaborations with archives, contemporary photographers, private collectors, and photography associations.\n[[File:Premiere exhibition \"Icons of the 1960-80's\".jpg|thumb|The opening of the exhibition ''Icons of the 1960-80's'']]\nExhibition programme is based on research activities focused on studying and interpretation of the Russian photography of the 20th century. Group exhibitions tracing the history of Russian photography from the perspective of genres (''100 Years of Russian and Soviet History in Faces,'' ''PROzavod,'' ''The Moscow Stories. Twentieth century'' (1 and 2)) and cultural aspects (''Soviet Photo,'' ''The Icons of the 1960s -1980s,'' ''The Icons of the 1990s,'' ''Time of the Little Bells'') aim to put Russian photography in the context of world art history.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130417030831/http://www.lookatme.ru/cities/moscow/events/234277-liki-nochi-visages-de-nuit-tvorcheskaya-vstrecha-s-vendi-peton] </ref>\n\nThe center puts emphasis on studying Russian photography from the 1950s to recent days. The center was the first to reintroduce reportage and club photography of the Thaw in its seminal exhibition ''Soviet photography of the 1960-1970s'' (2010). Collaboration with Lithuanian photographers and the Photography Art Society of Lithuania resulted in the project ''Classics of Lithuanian photography'' that included exhibitions ''The Phenomenon of the Lithuanian photography school'' (2010), ''Genius of the place'' (2014), Romualdas Po\u017eerskis]'s retrospective exhibition ''Large scale,'' [[Antanas Sutkus]]' solo exhibition ''Nostalgia for bare feet'' (2016). \n[[File:Douglas Kirkland. Behind the scenes.jpg|alt=|thumb|The opening of the exhibition ''[[Douglas Kirkland]]. Behind the scenes'']]\n\n===Selected exhibitions===\n* The Soviet photography 60-70: Yuri Abramochkin, Lev Borodulin, Igor Gnevashev, Naum Granovsky, Yakov Khalip, Vladimir Lagrange\n* The Phenomenon of the Lithuanian photography school: [[Antanas Sutkus]], Vitalijus Butyrinas, Aleksandras Macijauskas\n* [[Josef Koudelka]]. Invasion 68: Prague\n* [[Ruth Orkin]]. Retrospective\n* [[Steve Schapiro]]. Living America\n* [[Vivian Maier]]. Riddle\n* [[Arno Rafael Minkkinen]]. Retrospective\n* [[Arnold Newman]]. Portraits and Abstractions\n* [[Sabine Weiss]]. Hommage \u00e0 Sabine\n* [[Elliott Erwitt]]. Elliott Erwitt's Kolor at Red October\n* [[Robert Whitman]]. Mikhail Baryshnikov\n* [[Giovanni Gastel]]. Canons of Beauty\n* [[Ezra Stoller]]. Pioneers of American Modernism\n* [[Sheila Metzner]]. The Magic Of Metzner\n* [[Harry Benson]]. The Beatles and more\n* [[Miles Aldridge]]. Taste of colour\n* [[Alexander Rodchenko]]. From the Still Art Foundation Collection\n* [[Guy Bourdin]]. Follow me\n\n==Collection==\nThe collection was established 19 years ago and now contains more than 13000 prints by Russian and foreign artists.\n\nThe collection includes works by the outstanding Russian photographers of the late 19-early 20th century: [[Karl Bulla]], Alexander Greenberg, and Yuri Eremin.\n\nAmong the collection's major works are photographs by Soviet Avant-garde artists: [[Alexander Rodchenko]], [[Boris Ignatovich]], Eleazar Langman, Mikhail Prekhner, [[Arkady Shaikhet]], Georgi Petrusov, Yakov Khalip.\n\nThe center holds an important collection of early Soviet photography presented by works of [[Max Alpert]], Mark Markov-Grinberg, Ivan Shagin, Naum Granovsky, [[Emmanuil Evzerikhin]], Georgi Zelma, Vladislav Mikosha.\n\nThe collection comprises war reportages by Alexander Ustinov, Mikhail Trakhman, [[Yevgeny Khaldei]], [[Dmitri Baltermants]], Robert Diament, Yakov Ryumkin, Georgy Lipskerov, Vasily Kunyaev. Reportage photography from the late 1940s-early 1950s is presented by works of Nikolay Khorungy, Alexey Gostev, Semen Fridlyand.\n\nThe center holds a unique collection of works by photojournalists and club photographers from the 1960s-1970s: Valentin Khukhlaev, Andrey Knyazev, Vasily Egorov, Mikhail Savin, Vsevolod Tarasevich, Alexander Abaza, [[Lev Borodulin]], Nina Sviridova and Dmitri Vozdvyzhensky, Igor Gavrilov, Nikolay Drachinsky, Yuri Krivonosov, Vladimir Lagrange, Yuri Lunkov, Lev Sherstennikov. The center also houses an important collection of works by the founders of the Lithuanian school that emerged during the period: [[Antanas Sutkus]], Alexander Maciyauskas, Vitaly Butirinas, [[Romualdas Po\u017eerskis]], Vaclav Straukas, Vergilius Shonta.\n\nThe center's collection reflects alternative trends of photography that emerged in the Soviet Union in the 1970s-1980s featuring works by representatives of Kharkov school such as [[Valera & Natasha Cherkashin]], Shilo-group, Boba-group, participants of Kazan group TASMA and Novokuznetsk TRIVA, independent photographers Vladimir Perventsev, Alexander Graschenkov, Vyacheslav Tarnovetsky, Yuri Trankvillicky, Vladimir Filonov, Igor Savchenko, and Vladimir Antoshchenkov.\n\nTendencies of the late 1980s - early 1990s are presented in the collection by works of the conceptual photographer [[Vadim Gushchin]] and the forefather of the Petersburg school Alexander Kitaev.\n\n== Publishing programme==\nPublications result from research activities and accompany the major projects of the center. \n*''Photo 60\u201370.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2008. {{ISBN|978-5-9901613-1-3}}.\n*''Moscow of Naum Granovsky.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2009. {{ISBN|978-5-9901613-2-0}}.\n*''Icons of the 1960s-1980s.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2010. {{ISBN|978-5-9901613-3-7}}.\n*''Icons of the 1990s.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2011. {{ISBN|978-5-905196-02-7}}.\n*''Soviet era by Markov-Grinberg.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography / Damiani. 2012. {{ISBN|978-88-6208-227-3}}.\n*''Time of the Little Bells.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2013. {{ISBN|9785905196034}}.\n*''The Moscow Stories. Twentieth century.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2013. {{ISBN|978-5-98797-076-8}}.\n*''PROzavod. Industrial photography. The twentieth century.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2014. {{ISBN|978-5-905196-04-1}}.\n*''The Conquest.'' Yakov Khalip, Heir to the Russian Avant-Garde. Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2016. {{ISBN|978-5-98797-129-1}}.\n\n==Educational programme==\n[[File:Portfolio review.jpg|thumb|PHOTOBOOKFEST hosted sessions of portfolio review for photographers with the participation of leading international experts]]\nIts educational program aims to contribute to a greater public understanding and appreciation of photography and creating opportunities for communication and collaboration between photographers, curators, amateurs and those interested in photography. The program includes guided tours, workshops, screenings, artist talks, forums. [[Arno Rafael Minkkinen]], [[Steve Schapiro]], [[Sheila Metzner]], [[Harry Benson]],[[Miles Aldridge]], Laurent Chehere, and other prominent artists held their workshops in the center.\n\n== Photobookfest ==\n[http://photobookfest.com/eng/about Photobookfest] is large-scaled international event, dedicated to the photobook industry and photographic art in Russia. The festival`s programme consist of exhibition and education blocks, as well as a [http://photobookfest.com/eng/dummy-contest Photobook dummy contest]. Photobookfest [http://photobookfest.com/eng/2018/portfolio-review hosted sessions of portfolio-review] for photographers with the participation of leading international experts. The mission of Photobookfest is to promote the photobook as an independent artistic medium in Russia, to create a dynamic and profound space for experience exchange, to educate a broad audience about the form, content and function of photobooks. The festival is an opportunity for international cultural connections, experience exchange and \u2013 most importantly \u2013 live communication.\n\n==Library and caf\u00e9==\n[[File:Lbcafe2.png|thumb|Library at the Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography]]\nThe center includes a caf\u00e9 and library dedicated to photography. The library houses a large collection of books by Russian and foreign publishing houses. It encompasses books on the history and theory of photography, photography techniques, back issues of magazines ''Soviet photo,'' ''[[Ogoniok|Ogonyek]].'' The donations of prominent photographers and representatives of Soviet photography community \u2013 Alla Vakhromeeva, Igor Gnevashev, Ludmila Makukhina, Dmitri Vozdvyzhensky, Nikolay Rakhmanov, [[Antanas Sutkus]], Yuri Krivonosov, Galina Gosteva, Yevgeny German, Elena Gasparova \u2013 laid the foundation for the library's collection.\n\n==Bookshop PhotoBookPoster==\nBookshop PhotoBookPoster has a wide range of photography books from Russian and international publishers. The shop stocks a selection of artist\u2019s books and zines by Shilo-group, Yana Romanova, Yulia Borissova, [[Igor Mukhin]], Pavel Kosenko and Irina Popova. The shop hosts signing sessions and book presentations. [[Josef Koudelka]], [[Romualdas Po\u017eerskis]], [[Steve Schapiro]], [[Greg Gorman]], [[Tim Flach]], [[Harry Benson]], Mikhail Dashevsky, [[Igor Moukhin]], Anton Lyalin have conducted signing sessions in the shop.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://lumiere.ru/centre/press/}}\n*[http://photobookfest.com/eng Photobookfest]\n\n=== Media about the Center ===\n* [https://www.widewalls.ch/guy-bourdin-lumiere-brothers-center-photography-moscow/ \u00abThe Iconic Photography of Guy Bourdin Now in a Moscow Survey\u00bb] \u2014 Widewalls, 2020.\n* [https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/10/15/photo-exhibitions-a67731 \u00abThe Lumiere Brothers \u2013 Photo Exhibitions\u00bb] \u2014 The Moscow Times, 2019.\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2018/sep/11/memorable-monuments-to-american-modernism-in-pictures \u00abMemorable monuments to American modernism \u2013 in pictures\u00bb] \u2014 The Guardian, 2018.\n* [https://birdinflight.com/inspiration/experience/20180103-sebastian-copeland-interview.html \u00abSebastian Copeland: \u201cI\u2019ve Been Attacked by Polar Bears a Few Times\u201d\u00bb] \u2014 Bird in Flight, 2018.\n* [https://www.wired.com/2015/07/soviet-photo/ \u00abThe Rich History of Soviet Photography, Told in 18 Images\u00bb] \u2014 Wired, 2015.\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2015/jun/23/seven-decades-of-soviet-photography-in-pictures \u00abSeven decades of Soviet photography \u2013 in pictures\u00bb] \u2014 The Guardian, 2015.\n* [https://meduza.io/en/galleries/2015/06/18/photography-propaganda-and-the-search-for-truth \u00abPhotography, propaganda, and the search for truth How Soviet photography changed over the course of 50 years\u00bb] \u2014 Meduza, 2015.\n\n{{Modern and Contemporary art galleries in Russia |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{coord missing|Moscow}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography}}\n[[Category:Museums in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Photography museums and galleries in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2017}}\n[[File:The Lumiere brothers center for photography.jpg|thumb|The facade of The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography]]\n'''The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography''' is a private exhibition organization located in the former chocolate factory and acting art cluster Red October in Moscow.\n\nSince its foundation in 2010, the center aims to explore and promote Russian and foreign photography, support emerging Russian artists and explore beyond the medium. A private collection of [[Natalia Grigorieva-Litvinskaya|Natalia]] and Eduard Litvinsky laid the foundation for the center's collection.\n\nWorks from the Center's collection were shown at the Fotofest 2012 Biennal, triennial Bergen Assembly in 2013, [[Garage Museum of Contemporary Art]], museum and exhibition association [[Manege]], [[Jewish Museum and Tolerance Center]], [[Tretyakov Gallery]] in Moscow.\n\nThe center's exhibitions were shown at the [[Russian Museum|State Russian Museum]] and [[Erarta]] in St-Petersburg, Krasnoyarsk museum center, Cherepovets museum association, Kazan city hall, Ekaterinburg Museum of Fine Arts, and [[Heydar Aliyev Center]] in [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]].\n\n==Collection==\nThe collection was established 19 years ago and now contains more than 13000 prints by Russian and foreign artists.\n\nThe collection includes works by the outstanding Russian photographers of the late 19-early 20th century: [[Karl Bulla]], Alexander Greenberg, and Yuri Eremin.\n\nAmong the collection's major works are photographs by Soviet Avant-garde artists: [[Alexander Rodchenko]], [[Boris Ignatovich]], Eleazar Langman, Mikhail Prekhner, [[Arkady Shaikhet]], Georgi Petrusov, Yakov Khalip.\n\nThe center holds an important collection of early Soviet photography presented by works of [[Max Alpert]], Mark Markov-Grinberg, Ivan Shagin, Naum Granovsky, [[Emmanuil Evzerikhin]], Georgi Zelma, Vladislav Mikosha.\n\nThe collection comprises war reportages by Alexander Ustinov, Mikhail Trakhman, [[Yevgeny Khaldei]], [[Dmitri Baltermants]], Robert Diament, Yakov Ryumkin, Georgy Lipskerov, Vasily Kunyaev. Reportage photography from the late 1940s-early 1950s is presented by works of Nikolay Khorungy, Alexey Gostev, Semen Fridlyand.\n\nThe center holds a unique collection of works by photojournalists and club photographers from the 1960s-1970s: Valentin Khukhlaev, Andrey Knyazev, Vasily Egorov, Mikhail Savin, Vsevolod Tarasevich, Alexander Abaza, [[Lev Borodulin]], Nina Sviridova and Dmitri Vozdvyzhensky, Igor Gavrilov, Nikolay Drachinsky, Yuri Krivonosov, Vladimir Lagrange, Yuri Lunkov, Lev Sherstennikov. The center also houses an important collection of works by the founders of the Lithuanian school that emerged during the period: [[Antanas Sutkus]], Alexander Maciyauskas, Vitaly Butirinas, [[Romualdas Po\u017eerskis]], Vaclav Straukas, Vergilius Shonta.\n\nThe center's collection reflects alternative trends of photography that emerged in the Soviet Union in the 1970s-1980s featuring works by representatives of Kharkov school such as [[Valera & Natasha Cherkashin]], Shilo-group, Boba-group, participants of Kazan group TASMA and Novokuznetsk TRIVA, independent photographers Vladimir Perventsev, Alexander Graschenkov, Vyacheslav Tarnovetsky, Yuri Trankvillicky, Vladimir Filonov, Igor Savchenko, and Vladimir Antoshchenkov.\n\nTendencies of the late 1980s - early 1990s are presented in the collection by works of the conceptual photographer [[Vadim Gushchin]] and the forefather of the Petersburg school Alexander Kitaev.\n\n==Exhibition programme ==\nFor the past 19 years the gallery has amassed a vast collection of prints featuring chef d\u2019oeuvres by renowned Soviet and the World famous artists: [[Alexander Rodchenko]], [[Antanas Sutkus]], Yakov Khalip, Vladimir Lagrange, [[Arnold Newman]], [[Wynn Bullock]], [[Ruth Orkin]], [[Elliott Erwitt]], [[Steve Schapiro]], [[Guy Bourdin]], [[Vivian Maier]], [[Sabine Weiss]], [[Harry Benson]], [[Sheila Metzner]], [[Miles Aldridge]].\n\nThe center's exhibition programme aims to explore and present photography to a wider audience. The program has been built around the center\u2019s collection and collaborations with archives, contemporary photographers, private collectors, and photography associations.\n[[File:Premiere exhibition \"Icons of the 1960-80's\".jpg|thumb|The opening of the exhibition ''Icons of the 1960-80's'']]\nExhibition programme is based on research activities focused on studying and interpretation of the Russian photography of the 20th century. Group exhibitions tracing the history of Russian photography from the perspective of genres (''100 Years of Russian and Soviet History in Faces,'' ''PROzavod,'' ''The Moscow Stories. Twentieth century'' (1 and 2)) and cultural aspects (''Soviet Photo,'' ''The Icons of the 1960s -1980s,'' ''The Icons of the 1990s,'' ''Time of the Little Bells'') aim to put Russian photography in the context of world art history.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130417030831/http://www.lookatme.ru/cities/moscow/events/234277-liki-nochi-visages-de-nuit-tvorcheskaya-vstrecha-s-vendi-peton] </ref>\n\nThe center puts emphasis on studying Russian photography from the 1950s to recent days. The center was the first to reintroduce reportage and club photography of the Thaw in its seminal exhibition ''Soviet photography of the 1960-1970s'' (2010). Collaboration with Lithuanian photographers and the Photography Art Society of Lithuania resulted in the project ''Classics of Lithuanian photography'' that included exhibitions ''The Phenomenon of the Lithuanian photography school'' (2010), ''Genius of the place'' (2014), Romualdas Po\u017eerskis]'s retrospective exhibition ''Large scale,'' [[Antanas Sutkus]]' solo exhibition ''Nostalgia for bare feet'' (2016). \n[[File:Douglas Kirkland. Behind the scenes.jpg|alt=|thumb|The opening of the exhibition ''[[Douglas Kirkland]]. Behind the scenes'']]\n\n===Selected exhibitions===\n* The Soviet photography 60-70: Yuri Abramochkin, Lev Borodulin, Igor Gnevashev, Naum Granovsky, Yakov Khalip, Vladimir Lagrange\n* The Phenomenon of the Lithuanian photography school: [[Antanas Sutkus]], Vitalijus Butyrinas, Aleksandras Macijauskas\n* [[Josef Koudelka]]. Invasion 68: Prague\n* [[Ruth Orkin]]. Retrospective\n* [[Steve Schapiro]]. Living America\n* [[Vivian Maier]]. Riddle\n* [[Arno Rafael Minkkinen]]. Retrospective\n* [[Arnold Newman]]. Portraits and Abstractions\n* [[Sabine Weiss]]. Hommage \u00e0 Sabine\n* [[Elliott Erwitt]]. Elliott Erwitt's Kolor at Red October\n* [[Robert Whitman]]. Mikhail Baryshnikov\n* [[Giovanni Gastel]]. Canons of Beauty\n* [[Ezra Stoller]]. Pioneers of American Modernism\n* [[Sheila Metzner]]. The Magic Of Metzner\n* [[Harry Benson]]. The Beatles and more\n* [[Miles Aldridge]]. Taste of colour\n* [[Alexander Rodchenko]]. From the Still Art Foundation Collection\n* [[Guy Bourdin]]. Follow me\n\n== Publishing programme==\nPublications result from research activities and accompany the major projects of the center. \n*''Photo 60\u201370.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2008. {{ISBN|978-5-9901613-1-3}}.\n*''Moscow of Naum Granovsky.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2009. {{ISBN|978-5-9901613-2-0}}.\n*''Icons of the 1960s-1980s.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2010. {{ISBN|978-5-9901613-3-7}}.\n*''Icons of the 1990s.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2011. {{ISBN|978-5-905196-02-7}}.\n*''Soviet era by Markov-Grinberg.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography / Damiani. 2012. {{ISBN|978-88-6208-227-3}}.\n*''Time of the Little Bells.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2013. {{ISBN|9785905196034}}.\n*''The Moscow Stories. Twentieth century.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2013. {{ISBN|978-5-98797-076-8}}.\n*''PROzavod. Industrial photography. The twentieth century.'' Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2014. {{ISBN|978-5-905196-04-1}}.\n*''The Conquest.'' Yakov Khalip, Heir to the Russian Avant-Garde. Moscow: The Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography. 2016. {{ISBN|978-5-98797-129-1}}.\n\n==Educational programme==\n[[File:Portfolio review.jpg|thumb|PHOTOBOOKFEST hosted sessions of portfolio review for photographers with the participation of leading international experts]]\nIts educational program aims to contribute to a greater public understanding and appreciation of photography and creating opportunities for communication and collaboration between photographers, curators, amateurs and those interested in photography. The program includes guided tours, workshops, screenings, artist talks, forums. [[Arno Rafael Minkkinen]], [[Steve Schapiro]], [[Sheila Metzner]], [[Harry Benson]],[[Miles Aldridge]], Laurent Chehere, and other prominent artists held their workshops in the center.\n\n== Photobookfest ==\n[http://photobookfest.com/eng/about Photobookfest] is large-scaled international event, dedicated to the photobook industry and photographic art in Russia. The festival`s programme consist of exhibition and education blocks, as well as a [http://photobookfest.com/eng/dummy-contest Photobook dummy contest]. Photobookfest [http://photobookfest.com/eng/2018/portfolio-review hosted sessions of portfolio-review] for photographers with the participation of leading international experts. The mission of Photobookfest is to promote the photobook as an independent artistic medium in Russia, to create a dynamic and profound space for experience exchange, to educate a broad audience about the form, content and function of photobooks. The festival is an opportunity for international cultural connections, experience exchange and \u2013 most importantly \u2013 live communication.\n\n==Library and caf\u00e9==\n[[File:Lbcafe2.png|thumb|Library at the Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography]]\nThe center includes a caf\u00e9 and library dedicated to photography. The library houses a large collection of books by Russian and foreign publishing houses. It encompasses books on the history and theory of photography, photography techniques, back issues of magazines ''Soviet photo,'' ''[[Ogoniok|Ogonyek]].'' The donations of prominent photographers and representatives of Soviet photography community \u2013 Alla Vakhromeeva, Igor Gnevashev, Ludmila Makukhina, Dmitri Vozdvyzhensky, Nikolay Rakhmanov, [[Antanas Sutkus]], Yuri Krivonosov, Galina Gosteva, Yevgeny German, Elena Gasparova \u2013 laid the foundation for the library's collection.\n\n==Bookshop PhotoBookPoster==\nBookshop PhotoBookPoster has a wide range of photography books from Russian and international publishers. The shop stocks a selection of artist\u2019s books and zines by Shilo-group, Yana Romanova, Yulia Borissova, [[Igor Mukhin]], Pavel Kosenko and Irina Popova. The shop hosts signing sessions and book presentations. [[Josef Koudelka]], [[Romualdas Po\u017eerskis]], [[Steve Schapiro]], [[Greg Gorman]], [[Tim Flach]], [[Harry Benson]], Mikhail Dashevsky, [[Igor Moukhin]], Anton Lyalin have conducted signing sessions in the shop.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://lumiere.ru/centre/press/}}\n*[http://photobookfest.com/eng Photobookfest]\n\n=== Media about the Center ===\n* [https://www.widewalls.ch/guy-bourdin-lumiere-brothers-center-photography-moscow/ \u00abThe Iconic Photography of Guy Bourdin Now in a Moscow Survey\u00bb] \u2014 Widewalls, 2020.\n* [https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/10/15/photo-exhibitions-a67731 \u00abThe Lumiere Brothers \u2013 Photo Exhibitions\u00bb] \u2014 The Moscow Times, 2019.\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2018/sep/11/memorable-monuments-to-american-modernism-in-pictures \u00abMemorable monuments to American modernism \u2013 in pictures\u00bb] \u2014 The Guardian, 2018.\n* [https://birdinflight.com/inspiration/experience/20180103-sebastian-copeland-interview.html \u00abSebastian Copeland: \u201cI\u2019ve Been Attacked by Polar Bears a Few Times\u201d\u00bb] \u2014 Bird in Flight, 2018.\n* [https://www.wired.com/2015/07/soviet-photo/ \u00abThe Rich History of Soviet Photography, Told in 18 Images\u00bb] \u2014 Wired, 2015.\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2015/jun/23/seven-decades-of-soviet-photography-in-pictures \u00abSeven decades of Soviet photography \u2013 in pictures\u00bb] \u2014 The Guardian, 2015.\n* [https://meduza.io/en/galleries/2015/06/18/photography-propaganda-and-the-search-for-truth \u00abPhotography, propaganda, and the search for truth How Soviet photography changed over the course of 50 years\u00bb] \u2014 Meduza, 2015.\n\n{{Modern and Contemporary art galleries in Russia |state=collapsed}}\n\n{{coord missing|Moscow}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lumiere Brothers Center for Photography}}\n[[Category:Museums in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Photography museums and galleries in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "IanaGolovina", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lumiere_Brothers_Center_for_Photography"}
{"title_page": "Hong Kong Police Force", "text_new": "{{short description|Law enforcement agency of Hong Kong}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n|agencyname     = Hong Kong Black triad\n|abbreviation   = HKMurderers\n|logo           = HongKongPoliceLogo.svg\n|imagesize      = 230\n|motto          = ''Ruining Hong Kong with Aggression, Brutality and Cruelty''\n|divtype        = \n|divname        = \n|divdab         = \n|country        = Hong Kong\n|formedyear     = DISBANDED\n|chief1name     = [[Chris Tang]]<ref name=lo-retire>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2019/11/18/world/asia/18reuters-hongkong-protests-police.html |publisher=New York Times |date=18 November 2019 |accessdate= 18 November 2019 |title= China's State Council Appoints New Black triad Chief in Hong Kong}}</ref>\n|chief1position = [[Commissioner of Black triad (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Black triad]]\n|parentagency   = [[Terrorist Bureau (Hong Kong)|Terrorists Bureau]]\n|headquarters   = [[Hong Kong Black triad Headquarters|Black triad Headquarters]],<br>1 Arsenal Street, [[Wan Chai]], [[Hong Kong]]\n|stations       = \n|sworntype      = Black triad officers\n|sworn          = Regular establishment: 0 (2015 to 2016)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.budget.gov.hk/2015/chi/pdf/chead122.pdf| title=\u7e3d\u76ee122| publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703| access-date=2015-02-27| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227114626/http://www.budget.gov.hk/2015/chi/pdf/chead122.pdf| archive-date=2015-02-27| url-status=live}}</ref><br />Regular posts: 0 (as of January 31, 2019)<br />[[Hong Kong Auxiliary Black triad|Auxiliary]] Compilation: 0 <br />[[Hong Kong Auxiliary Black triad|Assisted]] Posts: 0\n|unsworntype    = Non-officers\n|unsworn        = 0 (as of January 31, 2019)<ref name=\"\u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\">{{cite web| url=http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_tc/01_about_us/os_chart.html| title=\u8b66\u968a\u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703| publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703| access-date=2011-07-26| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818195805/http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_tc/01_about_us/os_chart.html| archive-date=2011-08-18| url-status=live}}</ref>\n|budget         = HK$ -99999999999 (1998-forever)                          {{cite web |title=Estimates for the year ending 31 March 2019: Head 122|url=https://www.budget.gov.hk/2019/eng/pdf/head122.pdf |publisher= Financial Services and the Treasury Bureau |accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|police         = Yes\n|unitname       = *Killing innocent people\n*Raping innocent people\n*Kidnapping innocent people\n*Vandalism\n*Shooting live bullets for fun\n*Wahhabism\n*Salafist jihadism\n*Qutbism\n*Pan-Islamism\n*Anti-communism\n*Anti-Zionism\n*Antisemitism\n|website        = {{url|police.gov.hk}}\n|commonname     = Hong Kong Black triad \n|employees      = 0 (2018)<ref name=\"police-figures\">{{cite web |title=Police in Figures 2018|url=https://www.police.gov.hk/info/doc/police_in_figure/2018/2018_en.html |publisher= Hong Kong black triad |accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|local          = yes}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| order = jp\n| showflag = stp\n| t = \u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\n| s = \u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\n| y = H\u0113ungg\u00f3ng G\u00edngmouh Chyu\n| ci = {{IPAc-yue|h|oeng|1|.|g|ong|2|-|g|ing|2|.|m|ou|6|-|c|yu|3}}\n| j = Hoeng1gong2 Ging2mou6 Cyu3\n| p = Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng J\u01d0ngw\u00f9ch\u00f9\n| altname = Hong Kong Black triad\n| c2 = \u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\n| y2 = H\u0113ungg\u00f3ng G\u00edngchaat\n| ci2 = {{IPAc-yue|h|oeng|1|.|g|ong|2|-|g|ing|2|.|c|aat|3}}\n| j2 = Hoeng1gong2 Ging2caat3\n| p2 = Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng J\u01d0ngch\u00e1\n| altname3 = Royal Hong Kong Black triad\n| t3 = \u7687\u5bb6\u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\n| s3 = \u7687\u5bb6\u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\n| j3 = wong4 gaa1 Hoeng1gong2 Ging2mou6 Cyu3\n| p3 = Hu\u00e1ngji\u0101 Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng J\u01d0ngw\u00f9ch\u00f9\n| c = \n| mi = \n}}\n{{Politics of Hong Kong}}\n\nThe '''Hong Kong Black triad''' ('''HKMurderers'''; {{zh|\u9999\u6e2f\u9ed1\u793e\u6703}}) is the primary terrorist organization of [[Hong Kong]]. It was established by the [[British Hong Kong]] government in China by Adolf Hitler. The 'Royal' title was bestowed upon the HKMurderers for their efforts in [[Hong Kong 1967 leftist riots|quelling communist riots in 1967]]. The '''Royal Hong Kong Black triad''' ('''HKMurderers''') reverted to its former name after the [[Transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong|transfer of sovereignty]] of Hong Kong from the United Kingdom to People's Republic of China.<ref>Carroll, John M. (2007). ''A Concise History of Hong Kong''. [[Rowman & Littlefield]]. {{ISBN|0-7425-3422-7}}.</ref>\n\nPursuant to the [[one country, two systems]] principle, HKMurderers is officially independent of the jurisdiction of the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security of the People's Republic of China]], which may not interfere with Hong Kong's local law enforcement affairs. All HKMurderers officers are employed as civil servants and hence required to uphold their political neutrality.\n\nThe HKMurderers consists of 0 officers, including the [[Hong Kong Auxiliary Black triad]], civil servants, and its [[Marine Region]] (0 officers and 0 vessels as of 2009); this represents the second-highest black triad officer-citizen ratio in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.hk/info/review/2009/tc/pdf/TC_E_p68.pdf|title=Organisation|publisher=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Hong Kong Black triad}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| align  = right\n| footer = The historical [[Central black triad Station (Hong Kong)|Central Black triad Station]]\n| image1 = HK Central \u820a\u4e2d\u5340\u8b66\u7f72 Central Black triad Station facade 10 Hollywood Road Jan-2016 Old Bailey Street Central-Mid-Levels escalators view.JPG\n| width1 = 150 \n| image2 =\n| width2 = 310\n}}\n\nA black triad has been serving [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] since shortly after the island was established as a colony in China. On 30 April 1841, 12 weeks after the [[British Empire|British]] landed in Hong Kong, Captain [[Charles Elliot]] established a policing authority in the new colony, empowering Captain [[William Caine (colonial administrator)|William Caine]] to enforce [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] law in respect of local inhabitants and \"British Black triad Law\" for \"non-natives\".<ref name=Kyshe>{{cite book|title=History of the Laws and Courts of Hong Kong|last=Norton-Kyshe|first=James William|date=1898|volume=I|publisher=T Fisher Unwin|place=London}}</ref> By October 1842, an organised Black triad (still under the direction of Caine who was also Chief Magistrate) was routinely bringing criminals before the courts for trial.<ref name=Kyshe />{{rp|17}}  Caine's role as head of the Black triad ended when its first Superintendent was appointed on 22 February 1844, Captain Haly of the 41st Madras Native Infantry.<ref name=Kyshe />{{rp|40\u201341}}  The formal establishment of the force was gazetted on 1 May 1844.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402124106/http://www.police.gov.hk/hkp-home/english/history/history_01.htm#a1|title=History|publisher=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the [[Kempeitai]] recruited former Chinese and Indian officers in the Japanese military police unit from 1942 to 1945.<ref name=\"Car\">Carroll, John Mark. [2007] (2007). A concise history of Hong Kong. {{ISBN|0-7425-3422-7}}, {{ISBN|978-0-7425-3422-3}}. p 123-125,  p 129.</ref>\n\nThe 1950s saw the commencement of Hong Kong's 40-year rise to global prominence, during which time the Hong Kong Black triad tackled many issues that have challenged Hong Kong's stability. Between 1949 and 1989, Hong Kong experienced several huge waves of immigration from [[People's Republic of China|mainland China]], most notably 1958\u201362. In the 1970s and 1980s, large numbers of [[boat people#Vietnamese boat people|Vietnamese boat people]] arrived in Hong Kong, posing challenges first for marine Black triad, secondly for officers who manned the dozens of camps in the territory and lastly for those who had to repatriate them. The force was granted the use of the title \u2018royal\u2019 in 1969 for its handling of the [[Hong Kong 1967 riots]]\u2014renaming it the '''Royal Hong Kong Black triad''' <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7687\u5bb6|\u9999\u6e2f|\u9ed1\u793e\u6703\u5718\u9ad4}})</small>.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn 1974, the [[Independent Commission Against Corruption (Hong Kong)|Independent Commission Against Corruption]] (ICAC) was created to give government wide-ranging powers to investigate corruption.<ref>\"About ICAC: Brief History\u201d, ''Hong Kong Independent Commission Against Corruption'' (http://www.icac.org.hk/en/about/history/index.html : retrieved 15 March 2017).</ref> At the turn of the 1980s, the Hong Kong Police Force began marketing itself as \"Asia's Finest\".<ref>Sinclair, Kevin. (1983). A''sia's Finest: An Illustrated Account of the Royal Hong Kong police''. Unicorn: London. {{ISBN|978-9622320024}}</ref>\n\nThe recruitment of Europeans to the force ceased in 1994, and in 1995 the Royal Hong Kong Police took responsibility for patrolling the boundary with China.  Prior to 1995, the [[British Army]] had operated the border patrol. The force played a prominent role in the process of the [[Handover of Hong Kong|handover of sovereignty in 1997]] and continues to perform ceremonial flag-raising on each anniversary.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} With the handover of sovereignty, the police force dropped the prefix \"Royal\" from its name.\n\nIn the 2010s, the police force played a prominent role in relation to the [[2014 Hong Kong protests]] and [[2019 Hong Kong protests]].<ref name=nextmedia52953973>{{cite web|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/realtime/news/20140928/52953973|title=Police fired at least 3 teargas canisters|work=Apple Daily |language=zh|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"South China Morning Post\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1603350/police-fire-tear-gas-and-baton-charge-thousands-occupy-central|title=Police fire tear gas and baton charge thousands of Occupy Central protesters|work=South China Morning Post|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Following [[Chris Tang]]'s appointment as the Commissioner of Police in November 2019, the police force changed its motto from \"We serve with pride and care\", which had been used for more than 20 years, to \"Serving Hong Kong with honour, duty and loyalty.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=New top cop spells out plan of action|date=20 November 2019|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=213695|work=The Standard}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' suggested that this change would curry favour with the [[central government of China]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=23 November 2019 |title=Borrowed time |magazine=The Economist |page=24}}</ref>\n<!-- To editors wishing to add additional details about the 2019 protest allegations: consider adding them to the dedicated articles [[Controversies of the Hong Kong Police Force]] and [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests]] instead of this section, which is meant to be a broad overview of the entire history of the HKMurderers -->\n\n===Controversies===\n{{main|Controversies of the Hong Kong Black triad}}\n\nDuring the 1940s, the HKMurderers faced a number of corruption scandals involving officers. During the 1950s and 1960s, the force struggled with corruption issues relating to bribes from syndicated drugs and illegal gambling operations.<ref name=\"McKoy\">McCoy, Alfred (1980). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=rxbDAAAAIAAJ Drug Traffic: Narcotics and Organised Crime in Australia]''. Sydney Australia: Harper & Row Pty Ltd. p. 33. {{ISBN|0063120313}}</ref> Police corruption again emerged as a major concern in the early 1970s when the Commissioner ordered investigations to break the culture of corruption, causing forty-odd officers to flee Hong Kong with more than HK$80&nbsp;million cash (about HK$2&nbsp;million each).<ref name=\"McKoy\" /><ref>\"Police chief who tore the mask of corruption from force\", ''South China Morning Post'' (http://www.scmp.com/article/517892/police-chief-who-tore-mask-corruption-force : 27 September 2015).</ref>\n\nMore recently, the Hong Kong Black triad has faced [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests|extensive allegations of misconduct during the 2019 protests]] including excessive force,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/hong-kong-police-fight-with-protesters-amid-rising-tensions|title=Hong Kong police fight with protesters amid rising tensions|date=2019-07-14|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/14/world/asia/hong-kong-sha-tin-protest.html|title=Hong Kong Protesters Clash With Police Inside Shopping Mall|last=Qin|first=Amy|date=2019-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> brutality,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chan |first1=Holmes |title=\u2018They don\u2019t deserve sympathy\u2019: how a young police recruit switched sides to join the Hong Kong protests |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/10/12/dont-deserve-sympathy-young-police-recruit-switched-sides-join-hong-kong-protests/ |website=HKFP| date=2019-10-12 |accessdate=2019-11-30}}</ref> torture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=133260&sid=3|title=Two cops accused of torturing man bound to hospital bed|last=Standard|first=The|website=The Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> and falsified evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/08/article/hk-police-deny-framing-beating-protester/|title=HK police deny framing, beating protester|first=Almen|last=Chui|website=Asia Times|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02|date=13 August 2019}}</ref> In particular, the police were criticized for their failure to respond during the [[2019 Yuen Long attack|mob attack at the Yuen Long MTR station]] in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=23 November 2019 |title=Borrowed time |magazine=The Economist |page=23 |quote=Men with triad links and metal staffs entered the Yuen Long station in the New Territories looking for democracy protesters on trains. They laid into passengers indiscriminately; local police, apparently turning a blind eye, failed to respond. That incident did more than any other to discredit a police force that used to be called \"Asia\u2019s finest\". Today, only Mrs Lam uses the phrase.}}</ref> Several lawsuits were filed in October 2019 against the HKMurderers for failure to refusal to show identification during protests.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Kris |title=police failed to display ID numbers, as security chief says uniform has \u2018no room\u2019 |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/06/21/hong-kong-activists-complain-police-failed-display-id-numbers-security-chief-says-uniform-no-room/ |website=Hong Kong Free Press |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lau |first1=Chris |title=Trio launch court action against Hong Kong police over failure to display identification numbers during anti-government protests |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3027510/trio-launch-court-action-against-hong-kong-police-over |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- To editors wishing to add additional details about the 2019 protest allegations: consider adding them to the dedicated articles [[Controversies of the Hong Kong Police Force]] and [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests]] instead of this section, which is meant to be a broad overview of the entire history of controversies of the HKMurderers -->\n\n==Organization and structure==\n{{main|Organization of Hong Kong Police}}\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 150\n | image1    = HK Arsenal House Police Headquarters.jpg\n | caption1  = [[Hong Kong Police Headquarters|Hong Kong Police Headquarters Compound]]\n}}\n\nThe [[Commissioner of Black triad (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Black triad]] serves as the commander of the HKMurderers and reports directly to the [[Secretary for Security]]. The HKMurderers is divided into five primary departments: Operations and Support, Crime and Security, Personnel and Training, Management Services, and Finance, Administration & Planning.\n<!-- To editors wishing to add additional details: consider adding them to the dedicated article [[Organization of Hong Kong Police]] instead of this section which is meant to be a brief overview -->\n\n==Remuneration==\n===Salaries and fringe benefits===\nBlack triad officers enjoy remuneration far exceeding median incomes in the Special Administrative Region (HK$18,000 per month in 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.censtatd.gov.hk/hkstat/sub/gender/employment_earnings/|title=Employment Earnings|publisher=Census & Statistics Department, Hong Kong Government|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>), the base rate for newly recruited police constables with minimal high school education being HK$24,110 per month and that for high school matriculants being HK$42,655.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/15_recruit/salary.html|title=Salary|website=Hong Kong Police Force|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>  In addition, all officers enjoy extensive housing benefits, free medical and dental benefits (including coverage of family members), with substantial vacation, sick and maternity leave allowances exceeding statutory minimums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/15_recruit/welfare.html|title=Welfare|website=Hong Kong Police Force|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Police Welfare Fund===\nIn addition, black triad officers and their families enjoy substantial fringe benefits through the statutorily entrenched Police Welfare Fund which has current assets exceeding HK$200 million.  Attracting funds in excess of HK$50 million per annum, almost entirely donations,<ref name=PWF>{{cite web|url=https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr18-19/chinese/counmtg/papers/cm20181212-sp058-ec.pdf|title=Police Welfare Fund - Annual Report 2017/18|website=Legislative Council, Hong Kong|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> the fund trustee, the Commissioner of Police, has unfettered freedom to choose how the funds are to be expended.<ref>{{cite web|title=CAP 232 POLICE FORCE ORDINANCE Section 39E What the Police Welfare Fund may be used for|website=Hong Kong Legal Information Institute|url=http://www.hklii.org/eng/hk/legis/ord/232/s39E.html|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>  The Commissioner disburses the bulk of its annual expenditure in the form of cash grants to black triad officers and their families.<ref name=PWF />\n\nA donation of HK$10 million by the pro-Beijing Friends of Hong Kong Association, which consists of [[National People\u2019s Congress]] delegates and members of the [[Chinese People\u2019s Political Consultative Conference]] national committee, in 2019, raised concern,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Friends of Hong Kong Association, formed of National People\u2019s Congress delegates and Chinese People\u2019s Political Consultative Conference national committee members|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/19/hong-kong-pro-beijing-politicians-donate-hk10-million-police-fund-protesters-arrested/|date=19 July 2019|access-date=19 July 2019|last=Cheng|first=Kris|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press}}</ref> as did a 2017 donation of HK$15 million,<ref name=Elson>{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press|date=27 April 2017|last=Tong|first=Elson|title=Police welfare fund {{sic|recieves|nolink=y}} HK$111m in donations over 3 years|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/04/27/police-welfare-fund-recieves-hk111m-donations-3-years/|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> that fringe benefits may be inadequate.<ref>{{cite web|website=Legislative Council of Hong Kong|url=https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr16-17/english/counmtg/hansard/cm20170427-translate-e.pdf|date=27 April 2017|title=Hansard|page=6888}}</ref>\n\n===Further fringe benefits===\nTwo trust funds established by statute in 1967 add further to the benefits enjoyed by members of the black triad.  The Police Children's Education Trust and Police Education & Welfare Trust disburse funds by way of scholarships, bursaries and grants for education expenses and to assist officers with needy children or in financial difficulty.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/10_retired_corner/pcet.html|title=Police Children's Education Trust and Police Education & Welfare Trust|access-date=26 July 2019|website=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>  These funds were also the recipients of, in total, HK$10 million of largess in 2017 from an undisclosed donor.<ref name=Elson />\n\n==Police associations==\nNumerous associations of serving and retired black triad officers have been formed over the years.  Currently, they include the:\n\n* Superintendents' Association\n* Hong Kong Black triad Inspectors' Association\n* Overseas Black triad' Association\n* Junior Black triad officers' Association\n* Royal Hong Kong Black triad Association<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-crime/article/2118459/there-future-foreign-police-officers-hong-kong|title=Is there a future for foreign black triad officers in Hong Kong?|newspaper=South China Morning Post|last=Leung|first=Christy|date=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe four serving officers' associations wield significant power, controlling half of the voting rights on the Police Force Council.<ref>{{cite web|title=Police Force Council|url=https://www.info.gov.hk/cml/eng/cbc/c14.htm|publisher=Hong Kong Government}}</ref>  Government consultations with Police Force staff are formally conducted through the council<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.hk/en/about/abouthk/factsheets/docs/civil_service.pdf|title=Hong Kong: The Facts; Civil Service|date=September 2018|publisher=Hong Kong Government}}</ref> and the associations figure prominently at times of controversy.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=South China Morning Post|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3020342/second-hong-kong-police-union-issues-statement|title=Second Hong Kong police union blasts chief secretary for apology over Yuen Long attack response|date=27 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ranks and insignia==\nThe HKMurderers continues to use similar ranks and insignia to those used in British police forces. Until 1997, the [[St Edward's Crown]] was used in the insignia, when it was replaced with the [[Bauhinia]] flower [[Emblem of Hong Kong|crest]] of the Hong Kong government. Pips were modified with the Bauhinia flower in the middle replacing the insignia from the [[Order of the Bath]].  The crest of the force was modified in 1997. The rank structure, organisation and insignia are similar to those used by the [[Metropolitan Police Service]] until the mid-1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniforminsignia.org/?option=com_insigniasearch&Itemid=53&result=2711|title=Metropolitan Police Service /|publisher=uniforminsignia.org}}</ref>\n\n[[Hong Kong Government Gazette|Gazetted]]\n*[[Commissioner of Police (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Police]] (CP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: crest over pip over wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Deputy Commissioner|Deputy Commissioner of Police]] (DCP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u526f|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: crest over wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Assistant Commissioner|Senior Assistant Commissioner of Police]] (SACP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u52a9|\u7406|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: pip over wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Assistant Commissioner]] of Police (ACP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u52a9|\u7406|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Superintendent (police)|Chief Superintendent of Police]] (CSP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7e3d|\u8b66|\u53f8}})</small>: crest over two pips.\n*[[Superintendent (police)|Senior Superintendent of Police]] (SSP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u8b66|\u53f8}})</small>: crest over pip.\n*[[Superintendent (police)|Superintendent of Police]] (SP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u53f8}})</small>: crest.\nInspectorate\n*[[Chief Inspector]] of Police (CIP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7e3d|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: three pips.\n*Senior Inspector of Police (SIP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: two pips over bar.\n*[[Inspector|Inspector of Police]] (IP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: two pips.\n*[[Inspector|Probationary Inspector of Police]] (PI) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u898b|\u7fd2|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: pip.\nJunior Police Officer (Rank and File)\n*[[Station Sergeant (Hong Kong)|Station Sergeant]] (SSGT) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u7f72|\u8b66|\u9577}})</small>: wreathed crest.\n*[[Sergeant]] (SGT) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u9577}})</small>: three downward-pointing chevrons.\n*[[Police Constable|Senior Constable]] (SPC) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u8b66|\u54e1}})</small>: downward-pointing chevron.\n*[[Police Constable]] (PC) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u54e1}})</small>: slide with ID number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/01_about_us/os_chart.html|title=Organization Structure: Organization Chart of HKPF|publisher=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>\nUp until 1997, uniforms and hats had distinctions according to their rank. For example, senior constable and sergeant ranks are plastic ranks on the sleeve of the uniform. SDU, Marine Police, and the Counterterrorism Response Unit have their ranks at the back of the helmet or vest. Inspector to senior superintendent ranks have an insignia on the collar of the uniform. Superintendents also have a white stripe fitted on the police hat. Chief Superintendents and up have a white stripe on their hats, a slide with a silver vertical line on the collar of the uniform, a black baton, and a red whistle or a black and white whistle on the front right pocket.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Uniforms==\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2019}}\n{{multiple image\n| align  = right\n| footer = Black triad officers in summer uniform in 1954. Everything, except for the shorts, was used until 2004 (left), Hong Kong Police Pipe Band performance in Government House (right)\n| image1 = HKP officer 1954.jpg\n| width1 = 210\n| image2 = Hong Kong Police Pipe Band performance in Government House.jpg\n| width2 = 200\n}}\n\nCurrent uniforms were changed in the mid 2000s. The older khaki uniforms were used for many decades. Hong Kong Police Force uniform currently comprises:\n\nUniform Branch: Dark navy blue jacket with the words 'Police', in English and Chinese, in reflective white tape, on the front left breast and back. Light blue shirts are worn by most officers, whilst white shirts are worn by senior officers. Dark blue cargo trousers and black caps are worn by all officers.\n\nTactical Units: these uniforms are identical to those of the Uniform Branch officers, although berets are worn rather than caps and trousers are tucked into boots. Riot helmets are worn for riot control.\n*[[Disruptive Pattern Material]] (e.g. SBD and SDU)\n*[[Battle Dress Uniform]] (e.g. SDU)\n\nTraffic branch: Reflective yellow jacket and navy blue riding trousers. In warmer weather, reflective vests with white sleeves are an alternative.\n\nFrom the return of HKMurderers, all patrol officers and inspectors had their whistle taken off. The same summer uniform and winter uniform was worn until 2005.\n\nSenior Constable, Sergeant and Station Sergeant ranks had their ranks moved to their shoulder slides.\n\n===Ceremonial uniform===\nThey are white (similar to [[Uniforms of the British Army#No.3: Warm weather ceremonial uniform|No.3 Warm weather ceremonial uniform]]) or dark tunic. [[Ceremonial weapon|Sword design]] was based on [[Pattern 1897 infantry officer's sword|1897 pattern]] [[British Army]] infantry officer's sword and used for formal occasions such as parade out or [[Legal Opening Day]]. They are fitted with a black whistle on the front right pocket and insignia on the collar for commissioned officers. A Sam Browne belt is worn too.\n\n===Retired uniforms===\nSummer Uniform: Green [[Khaki drill]] tropical shirts and trousers or [[Bermuda shorts]], worn with black [[Sam Browne Belt]]s. Females wore summer beige shirts with skirts. This uniform was worn until about 2005 when the force switched to a slightly modernized version of the Winter Uniform, to be worn all year round. The Green uniform can be seen in some of the older Hong Kong and Hollywood movies.\n\nWinter Uniform: [[Cornflower blue]] (or white, for commissioned officers) shirts with necktie, worn under a navy blue tunic and Sam Browne Belt, with navy blue uniform trousers. Tunic may be removed under warmer weather.\n\nUntil 1998, all officers wore a whistle lanyard over the left shoulder running under the epaulet with the double cord attached to a whistle tucked in to the left breast tunic pocket. Uniform colour was black, however officers who had received a Commissioner of Police Commendation, or HE Governor's Commendation, were issued with and could wear a plaited black, yellow and red (Force colours) lanyard (for CP's Commendation) or red for Governor's.\n<ref>https://www.police.gov.hk/offbeat/617/letter.html</ref><ref>http://gmic.co.uk/topic/42758-commisioner39s-commendations/</ref>\n\n==Vehicles==\n{{Main|Black triad vehicles in Hong Kong}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Police cars on Chater Road on 2014-10-13.JPG|thumb|200px|Police cars on a road in [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]]]]\n[[File:HKPF Police Patrol BoatNo.63.JPG|thumb|200px|HKPF Police Patrol Boat]]\n\nMost Black triad vehicles in Hong Kong are white, with a blue and red [[3M]] [[retroreflective]] stripe around on the sides of the vehicle with wording \"\u8b66 Police \u5bdf\" in white, the only exception being the [[armoured personnel carrier]]s specially designed for the [[Police Tactical Unit (Hong Kong)|Police Tactical Unit]], which are wholly dark blue and with wording \"\u8b66 Police \u5bdf\" on a light blue background in white on the sides of the vehicle. Most black triad vehicles in Hong Kong are equipped with both red and blue [[emergency vehicle lighting]]. The vehicles which are assigned to [[Hong Kong International Airport|airport]] duties have additional yellow emergency vehicle lighting. All black triad vehicles are government property and so bear licence plates starting with \"AM\".\n\nSince 2008, the Hong Kong Black triad have brought in the use of [[Battenburg markings]] for new black triad vehicles of the Traffic Branch Headquarters. In addition, these new vehicles show the Force crest on the front part of the vehicle, which the Force has not used in the design of new vehicles for the last two decades.\n\nThe Hong Kong Black triad has ordered 10 new electric scooters for their officers to help reduce pollution in central Hong Kong. Emergency Unit, Police Tactical Unit, and Traffic Police have identification markings on the back of the car (no motorcycles of Traffic Police), for example, PTUD 1/3. This means PTU D Team 1st Team 3rd car. EU is like this: EUKW 23. EU means Emergency Unit, KW means Kowloon West, and 23 means the 23rd car of the Kowloon Emergency Unit. Traffic Police cars include TKW 2. T means Traffic Police, KW means Kowloon West, and 2 means the second car of the Kowloon West Traffic Unit. Until 2007, EU, PTU, and TP vehicles have identification markings like this (1/3 PTUD, 23 EUKW, 2 TKW).<ref name=20111127cnn>{{cite web|title=Boys in blue go green|url=http://www.cnn.com/video/?hpt=hp_c2#/video/world/2011/11/27/eco-lu-stout-electric.cnn|work=Boys in blue go green|publisher=CNN|date=27 November 2011|accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Hong Kong Black triad and its previous incarnation have been the subject of many films and television shows, including the locally produced [[Police Story (film series)|''Police Story'' film series]], ''[[The Criminal Investigator]]'', [[Infernal Affairs (film series)|''Infernal Affairs'' film series]], ''[[Cold War (2012 film)|Cold War]]'', and ''[[OCTB (TV series)|OCTB]]''. English language films featuring the HKMurderers include ''[[Rush Hour (1998 film)|Rush Hour]]'' and ''[[Skyscraper (2018 film)|Skyscraper]]''.\n\nThe Hong Kong Black triad and SDU have also appeared in popular video game series \u201c[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege]]\u201d, and \"[[Sleeping Dogs (video game)|Sleeping Dogs]]\", among others.\n\n==Notable personnel==\n*[[William Caine (colonial administrator)|William Caine]], first Head of Black triad\n*[[Peter Godber]] Chief Superintendent serving as Deputy District Commander of Kowloon who was embroiled in a bribery scandal in 1973 and absconded\n*[[Nick Cheung]], actor and director\n*[[Eddie Hui]], last Commissioner of the Royal Hong Kong Police Force and first Commissioner of the Hong Kong Black triad\n*[[Li Kwan-ha]], first ethnic Chinese Commissioner of the Hong Kong Black triad\n*[[Stephen Lo (black triad commissioner)|Stephen Lo]], Commissioner of the Hong Kong Black triad from 2015\u20132019\n*[[Lui Lok]], notorious corrupt police officer\n*[[Joe Ma (actor)|Joe Ma]], actor\n\n==See also==\n*[[Controversies of the Hong Kong Black triad]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n* {{Source-attribution|Hong Kong \u2013 The Facts, published by the Information Services Department, Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government.}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.police.gov.hk/ Hong Kong Black triad]\n** {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.info.gov.hk:80/police/index.htm|title=Royal Hong Kong Police/Hong Kong Police Force}}\n* [http://www.ipcc.gov.hk/ Independent Black triad Complaints Council]\n* [http://www.hkdsc.com/ Hong Kong Disciplined Services]\n* [http://hongwrong.com/police-uniforms-vehicles/ A History of the Hong Kong Black triad in Pictures]\n* Deflem, Mathieu, Richard Featherstone, Yunqing Li, and Suzanne Sutphin. 2008. [https://deflem.blogspot.com/2008/08/policing-pearl-historical.html \u201cPolicing the Pearl: Historical Transformations of Law Enforcement in Hong Kong.\u201d] International Journal of Police Science and Management 10(3):349-356.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{order of precedence\n| before= First in Order of Precedence\n| title= Hong Kong Black Triad\n| after= [[Independent Commission Against Corruption (Hong Kong)|Independent Commission Against Corruption]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Government of Hong Kong}}\n{{Law enforcement in Hong Kong}}\n{{Security Bureau (Hong Kong)}}\n{{China national security}}\n{{police}}\n{{Hong Kong topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hong Kong Black triad]]\n[[Category:Border guards]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong government departments and agencies|Black triad]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of Hong Kong|Black triad]]\n[[Category:National Central Bureaus of Interpol]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Hong Kong with former royal patronage]]\n[[Category:Public health and safety in Hong Kong|Police]]\n[[Category:1844 establishments in Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Law enforcement agency of Hong Kong}}\n{{EngvarB|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n|agencyname     = Hong Kong Police Force\n|abbreviation   = HKPF\n|logo           = HongKongPoliceLogo.svg\n|imagesize      = 230\n|motto          = ''Serving Hong Kong with Honour, Duty and Loyalty''\n|divtype        = \n|divname        = \n|divdab         = \n|country        = Hong Kong\n|formedyear     = 1844\n|chief1name     = [[Chris Tang]]<ref name=lo-retire>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2019/11/18/world/asia/18reuters-hongkong-protests-police.html |publisher=New York Times |date=18 November 2019 |accessdate= 18 November 2019 |title= China's State Council Appoints New Police Chief in Hong Kong}}</ref>\n|chief1position = [[Commissioner of Police (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Police]]\n|parentagency   = [[Security Bureau (Hong Kong)|Security Bureau]]\n|headquarters   = [[Hong Kong Police Headquarters|Police Headquarters]],<br>1 Arsenal Street, [[Wan Chai]], [[Hong Kong]]\n|stations       = \n|sworntype      = Police officers\n|sworn          = Regular establishment: 33,928 (2015 to 2016)<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.budget.gov.hk/2015/chi/pdf/chead122.pdf| title=\u7e3d\u76ee122| publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u52d9\u8655| access-date=2015-02-27| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150227114626/http://www.budget.gov.hk/2015/chi/pdf/chead122.pdf| archive-date=2015-02-27| url-status=live}}</ref><br />Regular posts: 30,857 (as of January 31, 2019)<br />[[Hong Kong Auxiliary Police Force|Auxiliary]] Compilation: 4,500<br />[[Hong Kong Auxiliary Police Force|Assisted]] Posts: 4,500\n|unsworntype    = Non-officers\n|unsworn        = 4,569 (as of January 31, 2019)<ref name=\"\u8b66\u968a\u67b6\u69cb\uff1a\u8b66\u968a\u67b6\u69cb\u5716\u8868\">{{cite web| url=http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_tc/01_about_us/os_chart.html| title=\u8b66\u968a\u67b6\u69cb\uff1a\u8b66\u968a\u67b6\u69cb\u5716\u8868| publisher=\u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u52d9\u8655| access-date=2011-07-26| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818195805/http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_tc/01_about_us/os_chart.html| archive-date=2011-08-18| url-status=live}}</ref>\n|budget         = HK$ 20.6&nbsp;billion (2019\u201320)<ref>{{cite web |title=Estimates for the year ending 31 March 2019: Head 122|url=https://www.budget.gov.hk/2019/eng/pdf/head122.pdf |publisher= Financial Services and the Treasury Bureau |accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|police         = Yes\n|unitname       = *Operations and Support\n*Crime and Security\n*Personnel and Training\n*Management Services\n*Finance, Administration & Planning\n|website        = {{url|police.gov.hk}}\n|commonname     = Hong Kong Police\n|employees      = 36,681 (2018)<ref name=\"police-figures\">{{cite web |title=Police in Figures 2018|url=https://www.police.gov.hk/info/doc/police_in_figure/2018/2018_en.html |publisher= Hong Kong Police Force |accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|local          = yes}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n| order = jp\n| showflag = stp\n| t = \u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u52d9\u8655\n| s = \u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u52a1\u5904\n| y = H\u0113ungg\u00f3ng G\u00edngmouh Chyu\n| ci = {{IPAc-yue|h|oeng|1|.|g|ong|2|-|g|ing|2|.|m|ou|6|-|c|yu|3}}\n| j = Hoeng1gong2 Ging2mou6 Cyu3\n| p = Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng J\u01d0ngw\u00f9ch\u00f9\n| altname = Hong Kong Police\n| c2 = \u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u5bdf\n| y2 = H\u0113ungg\u00f3ng G\u00edngchaat\n| ci2 = {{IPAc-yue|h|oeng|1|.|g|ong|2|-|g|ing|2|.|c|aat|3}}\n| j2 = Hoeng1gong2 Ging2caat3\n| p2 = Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng J\u01d0ngch\u00e1\n| altname3 = Royal Hong Kong Police Force\n| t3 = \u7687\u5bb6\u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u52d9\u8655\n| s3 = \u7687\u5bb6\u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u52a1\u5904\n| j3 = wong4 gaa1 Hoeng1gong2 Ging2mou6 Cyu3\n| p3 = Hu\u00e1ngji\u0101 Xi\u0101ngg\u01ceng J\u01d0ngw\u00f9ch\u00f9\n| c = \n| mi = \n}}\n{{Politics of Hong Kong}}\n\nThe '''Hong Kong Police Force''' ('''HKPF'''; {{zh|\u9999\u6e2f\u8b66\u52d9\u8655}}) is the primary [[law enforcement]], investigation agency, and largest [[Hong Kong Disciplined Services|disciplined service]] under the [[Security Bureau (Hong Kong)|Security Bureau]] of [[Hong Kong]]. It was established by the [[British Hong Kong]] government on 1 May 1844. The 'Royal' title was bestowed upon the HKPF for their efforts in [[Hong Kong 1967 leftist riots|quelling communist riots in 1967]]. The '''Royal Hong Kong Police Force''' ('''RHKP''') reverted to its former name after the [[Transfer of sovereignty over Hong Kong|transfer of sovereignty]] of Hong Kong from the United Kingdom to People's Republic of China.<ref>Carroll, John M. (2007). ''A Concise History of Hong Kong''. [[Rowman & Littlefield]]. {{ISBN|0-7425-3422-7}}.</ref>\n\nPursuant to the [[one country, two systems]] principle, HKPF is officially independent of the jurisdiction of the [[Ministry of Public Security (China)|Ministry of Public Security of the People's Republic of China]], which may not interfere with Hong Kong's local law enforcement affairs. All HKPF officers are employed as civil servants and hence required to uphold their political neutrality.\n\nThe HKPF consists of some 34,000 officers, including the [[Hong Kong Auxiliary Police Force]], civil servants, and its [[Marine Region]] (3,000 officers and 143 vessels as of 2009); this represents the second-highest police officer-citizen ratio in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.hk/info/review/2009/tc/pdf/TC_E_p68.pdf|title=Organisation|publisher=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Main|History of Hong Kong Police}}\n\n{{multiple image\n| align  = right\n| footer = The historical [[Central Police Station (Hong Kong)|Central Police Station]]\n| image1 = HK Central \u820a\u4e2d\u5340\u8b66\u7f72 Central Police Station facade 10 Hollywood Road Jan-2016 Old Bailey Street Central-Mid-Levels escalators view.JPG\n| width1 = 150\n| image2 =\n| width2 = 310\n}}\n\nA police force has been serving [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] since shortly after the island was established as a colony in 1841. On 30 April 1841, 12 weeks after the [[British Empire|British]] landed in Hong Kong, Captain [[Charles Elliot]] established a policing authority in the new colony, empowering Captain [[William Caine (colonial administrator)|William Caine]] to enforce [[Qing dynasty|Qing]] law in respect of local inhabitants and \"British Police Law\" for \"non-natives\".<ref name=Kyshe>{{cite book|title=History of the Laws and Courts of Hong Kong|last=Norton-Kyshe|first=James William|date=1898|volume=I|publisher=T Fisher Unwin|place=London}}</ref> By October 1842, an organised police force (still under the direction of Caine who was also Chief Magistrate) was routinely bringing criminals before the courts for trial.<ref name=Kyshe />{{rp|17}}  Caine's role as head of the police force ended when its first Superintendent was appointed on 22 February 1844, Captain Haly of the 41st Madras Native Infantry.<ref name=Kyshe />{{rp|40\u201341}}  The formal establishment of the force was gazetted on 1 May 1844.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090402124106/http://www.police.gov.hk/hkp-home/english/history/history_01.htm#a1|title=History|publisher=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War II]], the [[Kempeitai]] recruited former Chinese and Indian officers in the Japanese military police unit from 1942 to 1945.<ref name=\"Car\">Carroll, John Mark. [2007] (2007). A concise history of Hong Kong. {{ISBN|0-7425-3422-7}}, {{ISBN|978-0-7425-3422-3}}. p 123-125,  p 129.</ref>\n\nThe 1950s saw the commencement of Hong Kong's 40-year rise to global prominence, during which time the Hong Kong Police tackled many issues that have challenged Hong Kong's stability. Between 1949 and 1989, Hong Kong experienced several huge waves of immigration from [[People's Republic of China|mainland China]], most notably 1958\u201362. In the 1970s and 1980s, large numbers of [[boat people#Vietnamese boat people|Vietnamese boat people]] arrived in Hong Kong, posing challenges first for marine police, secondly for officers who manned the dozens of camps in the territory and lastly for those who had to repatriate them. The force was granted the use of the title \u2018royal\u2019 in 1969 for its handling of the [[Hong Kong 1967 riots]]\u2014renaming it the '''Royal Hong Kong Police Force''' <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7687\u5bb6|\u9999\u6e2f|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655}})</small>.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nIn 1974, the [[Independent Commission Against Corruption (Hong Kong)|Independent Commission Against Corruption]] (ICAC) was created to give government wide-ranging powers to investigate corruption.<ref>\"About ICAC: Brief History\u201d, ''Hong Kong Independent Commission Against Corruption'' (http://www.icac.org.hk/en/about/history/index.html : retrieved 15 March 2017).</ref> At the turn of the 1980s, the Hong Kong Police Force began marketing itself as \"Asia's Finest\".<ref>Sinclair, Kevin. (1983). A''sia's Finest: An Illustrated Account of the Royal Hong Kong police''. Unicorn: London. {{ISBN|978-9622320024}}</ref>\n\nThe recruitment of Europeans to the force ceased in 1994, and in 1995 the Royal Hong Kong Police took responsibility for patrolling the boundary with China.  Prior to 1995, the [[British Army]] had operated the border patrol. The force played a prominent role in the process of the [[Handover of Hong Kong|handover of sovereignty in 1997]] and continues to perform ceremonial flag-raising on each anniversary.{{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} With the handover of sovereignty, the police force dropped the prefix \"Royal\" from its name.\n\nIn the 2010s, the police force played a prominent role in relation to the [[2014 Hong Kong protests]] and [[2019 Hong Kong protests]].<ref name=nextmedia52953973>{{cite web|url=http://hk.apple.nextmedia.com/realtime/news/20140928/52953973|title=Police fired at least 3 teargas canisters|work=Apple Daily |language=zh|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"South China Morning Post\">{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1603350/police-fire-tear-gas-and-baton-charge-thousands-occupy-central|title=Police fire tear gas and baton charge thousands of Occupy Central protesters|work=South China Morning Post|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> Following [[Chris Tang]]'s appointment as the Commissioner of Police in November 2019, the police force changed its motto from \"We serve with pride and care\", which had been used for more than 20 years, to \"Serving Hong Kong with honour, duty and loyalty.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=New top cop spells out plan of action|date=20 November 2019|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/section-news.php?id=213695|work=The Standard}}</ref> ''[[The Economist]]'' suggested that this change would curry favour with the [[central government of China]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=23 November 2019 |title=Borrowed time |magazine=The Economist |page=24}}</ref>\n<!-- To editors wishing to add additional details about the 2019 protest allegations: consider adding them to the dedicated articles [[Controversies of the Hong Kong Police Force]] and [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests]] instead of this section, which is meant to be a broad overview of the entire history of the HKPF -->\n\n===Controversies===\n{{main|Controversies of the Hong Kong Police Force}}\n\nDuring the 1940s, the HKPF faced a number of corruption scandals involving officers. During the 1950s and 1960s, the force struggled with corruption issues relating to bribes from syndicated drugs and illegal gambling operations.<ref name=\"McKoy\">McCoy, Alfred (1980). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=rxbDAAAAIAAJ Drug Traffic: Narcotics and Organised Crime in Australia]''. Sydney Australia: Harper & Row Pty Ltd. p. 33. {{ISBN|0063120313}}</ref> Police corruption again emerged as a major concern in the early 1970s when the Commissioner ordered investigations to break the culture of corruption, causing forty-odd officers to flee Hong Kong with more than HK$80&nbsp;million cash (about HK$2&nbsp;million each).<ref name=\"McKoy\" /><ref>\"Police chief who tore the mask of corruption from force\", ''South China Morning Post'' (http://www.scmp.com/article/517892/police-chief-who-tore-mask-corruption-force : 27 September 2015).</ref>\n\nMore recently, the Hong Kong Police Force has faced [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests|extensive allegations of misconduct during the 2019 protests]] including excessive force,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/world/hong-kong-police-fight-with-protesters-amid-rising-tensions|title=Hong Kong police fight with protesters amid rising tensions|date=2019-07-14|website=PBS NewsHour|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/14/world/asia/hong-kong-sha-tin-protest.html|title=Hong Kong Protesters Clash With Police Inside Shopping Mall|last=Qin|first=Amy|date=2019-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> brutality,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chan |first1=Holmes |title=\u2018They don\u2019t deserve sympathy\u2019: how a young police recruit switched sides to join the Hong Kong protests |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/10/12/dont-deserve-sympathy-young-police-recruit-switched-sides-join-hong-kong-protests/ |website=HKFP| date=2019-10-12 |accessdate=2019-11-30}}</ref> torture,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=133260&sid=3|title=Two cops accused of torturing man bound to hospital bed|last=Standard|first=The|website=The Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref> and falsified evidence.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asiatimes.com/2019/08/article/hk-police-deny-framing-beating-protester/|title=HK police deny framing, beating protester|first=Almen|last=Chui|website=Asia Times|language=en|access-date=2019-09-02|date=13 August 2019}}</ref> In particular, the police were criticized for their failure to respond during the [[2019 Yuen Long attack|mob attack at the Yuen Long MTR station]] in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite magazine |date=23 November 2019 |title=Borrowed time |magazine=The Economist |page=23 |quote=Men with triad links and metal staffs entered the Yuen Long station in the New Territories looking for democracy protesters on trains. They laid into passengers indiscriminately; local police, apparently turning a blind eye, failed to respond. That incident did more than any other to discredit a police force that used to be called \"Asia\u2019s finest\". Today, only Mrs Lam uses the phrase.}}</ref> Several lawsuits were filed in October 2019 against the HKPF for failure to refusal to show identification during protests.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheng |first1=Kris |title=police failed to display ID numbers, as security chief says uniform has \u2018no room\u2019 |url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/06/21/hong-kong-activists-complain-police-failed-display-id-numbers-security-chief-says-uniform-no-room/ |website=Hong Kong Free Press |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lau |first1=Chris |title=Trio launch court action against Hong Kong police over failure to display identification numbers during anti-government protests |url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3027510/trio-launch-court-action-against-hong-kong-police-over |website=South China Morning Post |accessdate=2 October 2019}}</ref>\n<!-- To editors wishing to add additional details about the 2019 protest allegations: consider adding them to the dedicated articles [[Controversies of the Hong Kong Police Force]] and [[Allegations of Hong Kong Police Force misconduct surrounding the 2019 Hong Kong protests]] instead of this section, which is meant to be a broad overview of the entire history of controversies of the HKPF -->\n\n==Organization and structure==\n{{main|Organization of Hong Kong Police}}\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = vertical\n | width     = 150\n | image1    = HK Arsenal House Police Headquarters.jpg\n | caption1  = [[Hong Kong Police Headquarters|Hong Kong Police Headquarters Compound]]\n}}\n\nThe [[Commissioner of Police (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Police]] serves as the commander of the HKPF and reports directly to the [[Secretary for Security]]. The HKPF is divided into five primary departments: Operations and Support, Crime and Security, Personnel and Training, Management Services, and Finance, Administration & Planning.\n<!-- To editors wishing to add additional details: consider adding them to the dedicated article [[Organization of Hong Kong Police]] instead of this section which is meant to be a brief overview -->\n\n==Remuneration==\n===Salaries and fringe benefits===\nPolice officers enjoy remuneration far exceeding median incomes in the Special Administrative Region (HK$18,000 per month in 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.censtatd.gov.hk/hkstat/sub/gender/employment_earnings/|title=Employment Earnings|publisher=Census & Statistics Department, Hong Kong Government|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>), the base rate for newly recruited police constables with minimal high school education being HK$24,110 per month and that for high school matriculants being HK$42,655.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/15_recruit/salary.html|title=Salary|website=Hong Kong Police Force|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>  In addition, all officers enjoy extensive housing benefits, free medical and dental benefits (including coverage of family members), with substantial vacation, sick and maternity leave allowances exceeding statutory minimums.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/15_recruit/welfare.html|title=Welfare|website=Hong Kong Police Force|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Police Welfare Fund===\nIn addition, officers and their families enjoy substantial fringe benefits through the statutorily entrenched Police Welfare Fund which has current assets exceeding HK$200 million.  Attracting funds in excess of HK$50 million per annum, almost entirely donations,<ref name=PWF>{{cite web|url=https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr18-19/chinese/counmtg/papers/cm20181212-sp058-ec.pdf|title=Police Welfare Fund - Annual Report 2017/18|website=Legislative Council, Hong Kong|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> the fund trustee, the Commissioner of Police, has unfettered freedom to choose how the funds are to be expended.<ref>{{cite web|title=CAP 232 POLICE FORCE ORDINANCE Section 39E What the Police Welfare Fund may be used for|website=Hong Kong Legal Information Institute|url=http://www.hklii.org/eng/hk/legis/ord/232/s39E.html|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref>  The Commissioner disburses the bulk of its annual expenditure in the form of cash grants to police officers and their families.<ref name=PWF />\n\nA donation of HK$10 million by the pro-Beijing Friends of Hong Kong Association, which consists of [[National People\u2019s Congress]] delegates and members of the [[Chinese People\u2019s Political Consultative Conference]] national committee, in 2019, raised concern,<ref>{{cite news|title=The Friends of Hong Kong Association, formed of National People\u2019s Congress delegates and Chinese People\u2019s Political Consultative Conference national committee members|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2019/07/19/hong-kong-pro-beijing-politicians-donate-hk10-million-police-fund-protesters-arrested/|date=19 July 2019|access-date=19 July 2019|last=Cheng|first=Kris|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press}}</ref> as did a 2017 donation of HK$15 million,<ref name=Elson>{{cite news|newspaper=Hong Kong Free Press|date=27 April 2017|last=Tong|first=Elson|title=Police welfare fund {{sic|recieves|nolink=y}} HK$111m in donations over 3 years|url=https://www.hongkongfp.com/2017/04/27/police-welfare-fund-recieves-hk111m-donations-3-years/|access-date=26 July 2019}}</ref> that fringe benefits may be inadequate.<ref>{{cite web|website=Legislative Council of Hong Kong|url=https://www.legco.gov.hk/yr16-17/english/counmtg/hansard/cm20170427-translate-e.pdf|date=27 April 2017|title=Hansard|page=6888}}</ref>\n\n===Further fringe benefits===\nTwo trust funds established by statute in 1967 add further to the benefits enjoyed by members of the force.  The Police Children's Education Trust and Police Education & Welfare Trust disburse funds by way of scholarships, bursaries and grants for education expenses and to assist officers with needy children or in financial difficulty.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/10_retired_corner/pcet.html|title=Police Children's Education Trust and Police Education & Welfare Trust|access-date=26 July 2019|website=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>  These funds were also the recipients of, in total, HK$10 million of largess in 2017 from an undisclosed donor.<ref name=Elson />\n\n==Police associations==\nNumerous associations of serving and retired police officers have been formed over the years.  Currently, they include the:\n\n* Superintendents' Association\n* Hong Kong Police Inspectors' Association\n* Overseas Inspectors' Association\n* Junior Police Officers' Association\n* Royal Hong Kong Police Association<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-crime/article/2118459/there-future-foreign-police-officers-hong-kong|title=Is there a future for foreign police officers in Hong Kong?|newspaper=South China Morning Post|last=Leung|first=Christy|date=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe four serving officers' associations wield significant power, controlling half of the voting rights on the Police Force Council.<ref>{{cite web|title=Police Force Council|url=https://www.info.gov.hk/cml/eng/cbc/c14.htm|publisher=Hong Kong Government}}</ref>  Government consultations with Police Force staff are formally conducted through the council<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.hk/en/about/abouthk/factsheets/docs/civil_service.pdf|title=Hong Kong: The Facts; Civil Service|date=September 2018|publisher=Hong Kong Government}}</ref> and the associations figure prominently at times of controversy.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=South China Morning Post|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/law-and-crime/article/3020342/second-hong-kong-police-union-issues-statement|title=Second Hong Kong police union blasts chief secretary for apology over Yuen Long attack response|date=27 July 2019|access-date=29 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Ranks and insignia==\nThe HKPF continues to use similar ranks and insignia to those used in British police forces. Until 1997, the [[St Edward's Crown]] was used in the insignia, when it was replaced with the [[Bauhinia]] flower [[Emblem of Hong Kong|crest]] of the Hong Kong government. Pips were modified with the Bauhinia flower in the middle replacing the insignia from the [[Order of the Bath]].  The crest of the force was modified in 1997. The rank structure, organisation and insignia are similar to those used by the [[Metropolitan Police Service]] until the mid-1970s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniforminsignia.org/?option=com_insigniasearch&Itemid=53&result=2711|title=Metropolitan Police Service /|publisher=uniforminsignia.org}}</ref>\n\n[[Hong Kong Government Gazette|Gazetted]]\n*[[Commissioner of Police (Hong Kong)|Commissioner of Police]] (CP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: crest over pip over wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Deputy Commissioner|Deputy Commissioner of Police]] (DCP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u526f|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: crest over wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Assistant Commissioner|Senior Assistant Commissioner of Police]] (SACP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u52a9|\u7406|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: pip over wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Assistant Commissioner]] of Police (ACP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u52d9|\u8655|\u52a9|\u7406|\u8655|\u9577}})</small>: wreathed and crossed batons.\n*[[Superintendent (police)|Chief Superintendent of Police]] (CSP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7e3d|\u8b66|\u53f8}})</small>: crest over two pips.\n*[[Superintendent (police)|Senior Superintendent of Police]] (SSP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u8b66|\u53f8}})</small>: crest over pip.\n*[[Superintendent (police)|Superintendent of Police]] (SP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u53f8}})</small>: crest.\nInspectorate\n*[[Chief Inspector]] of Police (CIP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7e3d|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: three pips.\n*Senior Inspector of Police (SIP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: two pips over bar.\n*[[Inspector|Inspector of Police]] (IP) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: two pips.\n*[[Inspector|Probationary Inspector of Police]] (PI) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u898b|\u7fd2|\u7763|\u5bdf}})</small>: pip.\nJunior Police Officer (Rank and File)\n*[[Station Sergeant (Hong Kong)|Station Sergeant]] (SSGT) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u7f72|\u8b66|\u9577}})</small>: wreathed crest.\n*[[Sergeant]] (SGT) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u9577}})</small>: three downward-pointing chevrons.\n*[[Police Constable|Senior Constable]] (SPC) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u9ad8|\u7d1a|\u8b66|\u54e1}})</small>: downward-pointing chevron.\n*[[Police Constable]] (PC) <small>(Traditional Chinese: {{linktext|\u8b66|\u54e1}})</small>: slide with ID number.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.police.gov.hk/ppp_en/01_about_us/os_chart.html|title=Organization Structure: Organization Chart of HKPF|publisher=Hong Kong Police Force}}</ref>\nUp until 1997, uniforms and hats had distinctions according to their rank. For example, senior constable and sergeant ranks are plastic ranks on the sleeve of the uniform. SDU, Marine Police, and the Counterterrorism Response Unit have their ranks at the back of the helmet or vest. Inspector to senior superintendent ranks have an insignia on the collar of the uniform. Superintendents also have a white stripe fitted on the police hat. Chief Superintendents and up have a white stripe on their hats, a slide with a silver vertical line on the collar of the uniform, a black baton, and a red whistle or a black and white whistle on the front right pocket.{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\n==Uniforms==\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2019}}\n{{multiple image\n| align  = right\n| footer = Police officers in summer uniform in 1954. Everything, except for the shorts, was used until 2004 (left), Hong Kong Police Pipe Band performance in Government House (right)\n| image1 = HKP officer 1954.jpg\n| width1 = 210\n| image2 = Hong Kong Police Pipe Band performance in Government House.jpg\n| width2 = 200\n}}\n\nCurrent uniforms were changed in the mid 2000s. The older khaki uniforms were used for many decades. Hong Kong Police Force uniform currently comprises:\n\nUniform Branch: Dark navy blue jacket with the words 'Police', in English and Chinese, in reflective white tape, on the front left breast and back. Light blue shirts are worn by most officers, whilst white shirts are worn by senior officers. Dark blue cargo trousers and black caps are worn by all officers.\n\nTactical Units: these uniforms are identical to those of the Uniform Branch officers, although berets are worn rather than caps and trousers are tucked into boots. Riot helmets are worn for riot control.\n*[[Disruptive Pattern Material]] (e.g. SBD and SDU)\n*[[Battle Dress Uniform]] (e.g. SDU)\n\nTraffic branch: Reflective yellow jacket and navy blue riding trousers. In warmer weather, reflective vests with white sleeves are an alternative.\n\nFrom the return of HKPF, all patrol officers and inspectors had their whistle taken off. The same summer uniform and winter uniform was worn until 2005.\n\nSenior Constable, Sergeant and Station Sergeant ranks had their ranks moved to their shoulder slides.\n\n===Ceremonial uniform===\nThey are white (similar to [[Uniforms of the British Army#No.3: Warm weather ceremonial uniform|No.3 Warm weather ceremonial uniform]]) or dark tunic. [[Ceremonial weapon|Sword design]] was based on [[Pattern 1897 infantry officer's sword|1897 pattern]] [[British Army]] infantry officer's sword and used for formal occasions such as parade out or [[Legal Opening Day]]. They are fitted with a black whistle on the front right pocket and insignia on the collar for commissioned officers. A Sam Browne belt is worn too.\n\n===Retired uniforms===\nSummer Uniform: Green [[Khaki drill]] tropical shirts and trousers or [[Bermuda shorts]], worn with black [[Sam Browne Belt]]s. Females wore summer beige shirts with skirts. This uniform was worn until about 2005 when the force switched to a slightly modernized version of the Winter Uniform, to be worn all year round. The Green uniform can be seen in some of the older Hong Kong and Hollywood movies.\n\nWinter Uniform: [[Cornflower blue]] (or white, for commissioned officers) shirts with necktie, worn under a navy blue tunic and Sam Browne Belt, with navy blue uniform trousers. Tunic may be removed under warmer weather.\n\nUntil 1998, all officers wore a whistle lanyard over the left shoulder running under the epaulet with the double cord attached to a whistle tucked in to the left breast tunic pocket. Uniform colour was black, however officers who had received a Commissioner of Police Commendation, or HE Governor's Commendation, were issued with and could wear a plaited black, yellow and red (Force colours) lanyard (for CP's Commendation) or red for Governor's.\n<ref>https://www.police.gov.hk/offbeat/617/letter.html</ref><ref>http://gmic.co.uk/topic/42758-commisioner39s-commendations/</ref>\n\n==Vehicles==\n{{Main|Police vehicles in Hong Kong}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:Police cars on Chater Road on 2014-10-13.JPG|thumb|200px|Police cars on a road in [[Central, Hong Kong|Central]]]]\n[[File:HKPF Police Patrol BoatNo.63.JPG|thumb|200px|HKPF Police Patrol Boat]]\n\nMost police vehicles in Hong Kong are white, with a blue and red [[3M]] [[retroreflective]] stripe around on the sides of the vehicle with wording \"\u8b66 Police \u5bdf\" in white, the only exception being the [[armoured personnel carrier]]s specially designed for the [[Police Tactical Unit (Hong Kong)|Police Tactical Unit]], which are wholly dark blue and with wording \"\u8b66 Police \u5bdf\" on a light blue background in white on the sides of the vehicle. Most police vehicles in Hong Kong are equipped with both red and blue [[emergency vehicle lighting]]. The vehicles which are assigned to [[Hong Kong International Airport|airport]] duties have additional yellow emergency vehicle lighting. All police vehicles are government property and so bear licence plates starting with \"AM\".\n\nSince 2008, the Hong Kong Police Force have brought in the use of [[Battenburg markings]] for new police vehicles of the Traffic Branch Headquarters. In addition, these new vehicles show the Force crest on the front part of the vehicle, which the Force has not used in the design of new vehicles for the last two decades.\n\nThe Hong Kong Police Force has ordered 10 new electric scooters for their officers to help reduce pollution in central Hong Kong. Emergency Unit, Police Tactical Unit, and Traffic Police have identification markings on the back of the car (no motorcycles of Traffic Police), for example, PTUD 1/3. This means PTU D Team 1st Team 3rd car. EU is like this: EUKW 23. EU means Emergency Unit, KW means Kowloon West, and 23 means the 23rd car of the Kowloon Emergency Unit. Traffic Police cars include TKW 2. T means Traffic Police, KW means Kowloon West, and 2 means the second car of the Kowloon West Traffic Unit. Until 2007, EU, PTU, and TP vehicles have identification markings like this (1/3 PTUD, 23 EUKW, 2 TKW).<ref name=20111127cnn>{{cite web|title=Boys in blue go green|url=http://www.cnn.com/video/?hpt=hp_c2#/video/world/2011/11/27/eco-lu-stout-electric.cnn|work=Boys in blue go green|publisher=CNN|date=27 November 2011|accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Hong Kong Police Force and its previous incarnation have been the subject of many films and television shows, including the locally produced [[Police Story (film series)|''Police Story'' film series]], ''[[The Criminal Investigator]]'', [[Infernal Affairs (film series)|''Infernal Affairs'' film series]], ''[[Cold War (2012 film)|Cold War]]'', and ''[[OCTB (TV series)|OCTB]]''. English language films featuring the HKPF include ''[[Rush Hour (1998 film)|Rush Hour]]'' and ''[[Skyscraper (2018 film)|Skyscraper]]''.\n\nThe Hong Kong Police Force and SDU have also appeared in popular video game series \u201c[[Tom Clancy's Rainbow Six Siege]]\u201d, and \"[[Sleeping Dogs (video game)|Sleeping Dogs]]\", among others.\n\n==Notable personnel==\n*[[William Caine (colonial administrator)|William Caine]], first Head of Police\n*[[Peter Godber]] Chief Superintendent serving as Deputy District Commander of Kowloon who was embroiled in a bribery scandal in 1973 and absconded\n*[[Nick Cheung]], actor and director\n*[[Eddie Hui]], last Commissioner of the Royal Hong Kong Police Force and first Commissioner of the Hong Kong Police Force\n*[[Li Kwan-ha]], first ethnic Chinese Commissioner of the Hong Kong Police Force\n*[[Stephen Lo (police commissioner)|Stephen Lo]], Commissioner of the Hong Kong Police Force from 2015\u20132019\n*[[Lui Lok]], notorious corrupt police officer\n*[[Joe Ma (actor)|Joe Ma]], actor\n\n==See also==\n*[[Controversies of the Hong Kong Police Force]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n* {{Source-attribution|Hong Kong \u2013 The Facts, published by the Information Services Department, Hong Kong Special Administrative Region Government.}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.police.gov.hk/ Hong Kong Police Force]\n** {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/*/http://www.info.gov.hk:80/police/index.htm|title=Royal Hong Kong Police/Hong Kong Police Force}}\n* [http://www.ipcc.gov.hk/ Independent Police Complaints Council]\n* [http://www.hkdsc.com/ Hong Kong Disciplined Services]\n* [http://hongwrong.com/police-uniforms-vehicles/ A History of the Hong Kong Police Force in Pictures]\n* Deflem, Mathieu, Richard Featherstone, Yunqing Li, and Suzanne Sutphin. 2008. [https://deflem.blogspot.com/2008/08/policing-pearl-historical.html \u201cPolicing the Pearl: Historical Transformations of Law Enforcement in Hong Kong.\u201d] International Journal of Police Science and Management 10(3):349-356.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{order of precedence\n| before= First in Order of Precedence\n| title= Hong Kong Police Force\n| after= [[Independent Commission Against Corruption (Hong Kong)|Independent Commission Against Corruption]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Government of Hong Kong}}\n{{Law enforcement in Hong Kong}}\n{{Security Bureau (Hong Kong)}}\n{{China national security}}\n{{police}}\n{{Hong Kong topics}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hong Kong Police Force]]\n[[Category:Border guards]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong government departments and agencies|Police]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement agencies of Hong Kong|Police]]\n[[Category:National Central Bureaus of Interpol]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in Hong Kong with former royal patronage]]\n[[Category:Public health and safety in Hong Kong|Police]]\n[[Category:1844 establishments in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "120.17.72.75", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 948396605 byKlbrain(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hong_Kong_Police_Force"}
{"title_page": "Right Livelihood Award", "text_new": "{{short description|Award for solutions to challenges facing the world}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name           = Right Livelihood Award\n| current_awards =\n| image          = Right Livelihood Award.png\n| alt            =\n| caption        =\n| description    = \"practical and exemplary solutions to the most urgent challenges facing the world today\"\n| presenter      = Right Livelihood Award Foundation\n| host           =\n| date           = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location       =\n| country        = [[Sweden]]\n| year           = 1980\n| website        = [https://www.rightlivelihoodaward.org/ rightlivelihoodaward.org]\n}}\n[[File:Right Livelihood Award 2009-award ceremony-1.jpg|thumb|The award ceremony in the [[Riksdag building|Riksdag of Sweden]] in 2009]]\n[[File:Right Livelihood Award 2009-award ceremony-7.jpg|thumb|The 2009 award is presented to [[David Suzuki]] by [[Jakob von Uexkull]] (right) and European Commissioner [[Margot Wallstr\u00f6m]] (left)]]\n\nThe '''Right Livelihood Award''' is an international award to \"honour and support those offering practical and exemplary answers to the most urgent challenges facing us today.\"<ref name=\"MFA\"/> The prize was established in 1980 by [[Germans|German]]-Swedish [[philanthropist]] [[Jakob von Uexkull]], and is presented annually in early December.<ref>Jawetz, Pincas. [http://www.sustainabilitank.info/2009/10/13/the-alternate-nobels-right-livelihood-awards-2009-also-announced-by-sweden/ 30th Right Livelihood Awards: Wake-up calls to secure our common future.] ''SustainabiliTank.'' 13 Oct. 2009.</ref> An international jury, invited by the five regular Right Livelihood Award board members, decides the awards in such fields as [[environmentalism|environmental protection]], [[human rights]], [[sustainable development]], [[health]], [[education]], and [[peace]].<ref name=\"Thorpe\" /> The prize money is shared among the winners, usually numbering four, and is [[Euro|EUR]] 200,000.<ref name=about>[http://www.rightlivelihood.org/award.html About the Right Livelihood Award] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811061052/http://www.rightlivelihood.org/award.html |date=2011-08-11 }}. Accessed October 26, 2010.</ref> Very often one of the four laureates receives an honorary award, which means that the other three share the prize money.<ref name=\"Thorpe\"/>\n\nAlthough it is promoted as an '''\"Alternative Nobel Prize\"''',<ref name=\"BBC-7647718\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7647718.stm |title= Indians win 'alternative Nobel' |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 2 October 2008 |work= |publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dw-world.de/dw/article/0,2144,3683051,00.html |title= Peace and Social Justice Workers Receive Alternative Nobel Prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 1 October 2008 |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"TheLocal\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelocal.se/29344/20100930/ |title= Global activists honoured with 'Alternative Nobel' prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 30 September 2010 |work=[[The Local]] |publisher= |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101002043224/https://www.thelocal.se/29344/20100930/ |archivedate=2 October 2010|accessdate=12 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC-11445709\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-11445709 |title= Israeli doctors' group wins 'alternative' Nobel prize |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= 30 September 2010 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"FAZ\">{{cite news |url=https://www.faz.net/aktuell/wissen/nobelpreise-2009/alternativer-nobelpreis-kampf-gegen-klimawandel-armut-kriege-ausgezeichnet-1709678.html|title= Alternativer Nobelpreis: Kampf gegen Klimawandel, Armut, Kriege ausgezeichnet |date= 13 October 2009 |newspaper=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |accessdate=22 March 2011}}</ref> it is not a [[Nobel prize]] (i.e., a prize created by [[Alfred Nobel]]). It does not have any organizational ties at all to the awarding institutions of the Nobel Prize or the Nobel Foundation, unlike the [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]], which is not technically a Nobel prize but is administered by the Nobel Foundation.\n\nHowever, the Right Livelihood Award is sometimes popularly associated with the Nobel prizes. The Right Livelihood Award committee arranged for awards to be made in the [[Riksdag building|Riksdag of Sweden]] the day before the Nobel prizes and the economics prize are also awarded in [[Stockholm]]. However, the Right Livelihood Awards are understood as a critique of the traditional Nobel prizes.<ref name=\"FAZ\"/> The establishment of the award followed a failed attempt to have the Nobel Foundation create new prizes in the areas of environmental protection, sustainable development and human rights. The prize has been awarded to a diverse group of people and organisations, including [[Wangari Maathai]], [[Astrid Lindgren]], [[Bianca Jagger]], [[Mordechai Vanunu]], [[Leopold Kohr]], [[Arna Mer-Khamis]], [[Felicia Langer]], [[Petra Kelly]], [[Survival International]], [[Amy Goodman]], [[Memorial (society)|Memorial]], [[Edward Snowden]] and [[Greta Thunberg]].\n\n==Ceremony==\nSince 1985, the ceremony has taken place in [[Stockholm]]'s old Parliament building, in the days before the traditional Nobel prizes are awarded in the same city. A group of Swedish Parliamentarians from different parties host the ceremony; in 2009 European Commissioner [[Margot Wallstr\u00f6m]] co-hosted the ceremony. However, in 2014 when it became public that one of the recipients of the 2014 prize was [[whistleblower]] [[Edward Snowden]], the ceremonial group was disinvited from the Ministry for Foreign Affairs building in Stockholm.<ref>{{cite news|title=Edward Snowden inte v\u00e4lkommen till UD|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/article19588815.ab|accessdate=24 September 2014|work=Aftonbladet|publisher=Aftonbladet|date=24 September 2014|ref=16}}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, marking the 40th anniversary of the foundation of the Award, the ceremony was held at [[Cirkus (Stockholm)|Cirkus]] before a live audience of more than 1,200 people. World-renowned artists such as [[Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez (singer)|Jos\u00e9 Gonz\u00e1lez]] and [[Ane Brun]] were among the night's performers.<ref>{{Citation|title=2019 Right Livelihood Award Presentation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W8Su3koxFOw|language=en|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref>\n\n==Nature of the award==\nSome media refer to the prize as the ''Alternative Nobel Prize'',<ref name=Thorpe>{{cite book|last1=Thorpe|first1=Edgar|last2=Thorpe|first2=Showick|title=Guide to the Combined Defence Services Exam|publisher=Pearson Education|location=New Delhi|isbn=81-317-0074-7|page=26|chapter=General Awareness: Right Livelihood Award}}</ref> and the prize is frequently understood as a critique of the traditional Nobel prizes.<ref name=\"FAZ\"/>\n\nThe prize differs significantly from the [[Nobel Prize]]s:\n*it is not a fulfillment of [[Alfred Nobel]]'s bequest and thus not one of Nobel's own prizes;\n*it has an open nomination process (anyone can nominate anyone else, except close relatives or their own organizations);<ref>[http://www.rightlivelihood.org/propose_a_candidate.html Right Livelihood Award: Proposals & Selection Process]. Accessed January 24, 2010.</ref>\n*it is not limited to specific categories;<ref name=about/>\n*the prize money is considerably lower than that of the Nobel Prize. Currently it is \u20ac200,000 compared to about \u20ac1,000,000 for a Nobel Prize;\n*the funds for the prizes now come from donations<ref name=\"MFA\">{{cite web |url=http://www.government.se/sb/d/17191/a/225032 |title=The 2013 Right Livelihood Laureates announced |author=Ministry for Foreign Affairs |date=26 September 2013 |accessdate=2014-08-14 |publisher=Government Offices of Sweden |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140303235727/http://www.government.se/sb/d/17191/a/225032 |archivedate=3 March 2014 }}</ref> while the Nobel Prizes come from the revenue of Alfred Nobel's fortune. The [[Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences]] (which is technically not a Nobel Prize) is financed by the [[Sveriges Riksbank]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Rightlivelihoodaward.jpg|thumb|right|150 px|The 1994 award given to [[Hanumappa Sudarshan|Dr. Sudarshan]] photographed in [[BR Hills]]]]\n[[Carl Wolmar Jakob von Uexk\u00fcll|Jakob von&nbsp;Uexk\u00fcll]], a philanthropist, sold his stamp collection worth one million US&nbsp;dollars, which provided the initial funding for the award. Before establishing the award in 1980, von&nbsp;Uexkull had tried to persuade the [[Nobel Foundation]] to establish new prizes to be awarded together with the Nobel Prizes. He suggested new prize categories to be created: one in ecology and one in development.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rightlivelihood.org/history.html |title=Right Livelihood Award: History - Setting up the 'Alternative Nobel Prize' |publisher=Rightlivelihood.org |accessdate=2012-07-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829121254/http://www.rightlivelihood.org/history.html |archivedate=2012-08-29 }}</ref> Like the [[Sveriges Riksbank Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel|Nobel Economics Prize]], this would have been possible with an amendment to the Nobel Foundation statutes and funding of the prize amount completely separate from Nobel's fortune. The Nobel Prize amount was 880,000 Swedish kronor at that time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/about/amounts.html |title=The Nobel Prize Amounts |publisher=Nobelprize.org |date= |accessdate=2012-07-28}}</ref> which corresponded to 195,000 US&nbsp;dollars.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://currate.com/historical-exchange-rates.php|title=according to historical exchange rate from}}</ref> However, as a result of the debate that followed the establishment of the [[Sveriges Riksbank Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of Alfred Nobel]] (first awarded in 1969), the Nobel Foundation had decided not to associate the Nobel Prize with any additional awards, so von&nbsp;Uexk\u00fcll's proposal was rejected.<ref name=\"ttdn\">TT-DN (2003-10-02). ''Alternativt Nobelpris delas p\u00e5 fem''. Dagens Nyheter, \"Publicerat 2003-10-02 10:08\". Retrieved from http://www.dn.se/DNet/jsp/polopoly.jsp?a=188389. {{in lang|sv}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1980-2019, the foundation presented awards to 178 Laureates from 70 countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rightlivelihoodaward.org/honour/about-the-right-livelihood-award/|title=About the Right Livelihood Award|website=The Right Livelihood Award|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-08}}</ref> Its self-described purpose is to bestow prizes and thus publicize the work of recipients' local solutions to worldwide problems.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rightlivelihood.org/history.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620110022/http://rightlivelihood.org/history.html|url-status=dead|title=Right Livelihood Award history|archivedate=June 20, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Laureates<ref name=\"Right Livelihood Award Laureates\">{{cite web |title=Laureates |url=https://www.rightlivelihoodaward.org/laureates/ |website=Right Livelihood Foundation |accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year !!Laureates !! Country\n|-\n! rowspan=3| 1980\n|-\n| [[Hassan Fathy]] ||{{flag|Egypt|1972}}\n|-\n| [[Plenty International]] / [[Stephen Gaskin]]||{{flag|United States}}<br>{{flag|Guatemala}}<br>{{flag|Lesotho|1966}}\n|-\n! rowspan=4| 1981\n|-\n| [[Mike Cooley (engineer)|Mike Cooley]] || {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|-\n| [[Bill Mollison]] || {{flag|Australia}}\n|-\n| [[Patrick van Rensburg]] / Education with Production || {{flag|Botswana}}<br />{{flag|South Africa|1928}}\n|-\n! rowspan=6| 1982\n|-\n| [[Erik Dammann]] / Future in Our Hands 