{"title_page": "Dave Fanning", "text_new": "{{other people||David Fanning (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Dave Fanning\n|image         = Dave Fanning 2015 (cropped).jpg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Dave Fanning at 2015 Web Summit Music Stage\n|birth_name    = David Fanning\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1956|02|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n|death_place   =\n|body_discovered =\n|death_cause   =\n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence     =\n|nationality   = Irish\n|citizenship   =\n|other_names   =\n|known_for     = Music industry work, friendship with [[U2]], ''Fanning's Fab 50''\n|education     = English and Philosophy degree/Higher Diploma in Education\n|alma_mater    = [[University College, Dublin]]\n|employer      = [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]\n|occupation    = Radio and television presenter\n|years_active  =\n|home_town     =\n|title         =\n|salary        =\n|networth      =\n|height        =\n|weight        =\n|term          =\n|predecessor   =\n|successor     =\n|party         =\n|opponents     =\n|boards        =\n|religion      =\n|spouse        = Ursula Courtney\n|partner       =\n|children      = Jack, Robert and Hayley\n|parents       =\n|relations     =\n|callsign      =\n|signature     =\n|website       =\n|footnotes     =\n}}\n'''David Fanning''' (born 27 February 1956) is an Irish television and radio broadcaster, rock journalist, DJ, film critic and author. Fanning currently hosts weekend midday magazine/chat show ''[[The Dave Fanning Show]]'' on the Irish national radio station [[RT\u00c9 2fm]] and a number of [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] programmes. He regularly deputises on RT\u00c9 Radio 1 across a range of primetime programmes and also presented his own Monday-Friday 9&nbsp;am show ''Mornings With Dave Fanning'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mornings with Dave Fanning |url=https://www.rte.ie/radio1/the-john-murray-show/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann}}</ref>\n\nDue to his friendship with [[U2]], Fanning has for four decades been granted the first airing of any of the band's new singles before anyone else in the world,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0116/415914-u2/|title=World premiere for new U2 on RT\u00c9 2fm|date=16 January 2009|accessdate=16 January 2009|publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303134318/http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0116/415914-u2/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> with band members often calling Fanning to tell him what they are doing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8469694.stm|title=U2 and Jay-Z record song for Haiti|date=20 January 2010|accessdate=24 January 2010|publisher=BBC}}</ref> He has presented more than twenty different TV shows for [[RT\u00c9 Television]], from ''[[2TV]]'' to ''[[The Movie Show (Irish TV series)|The Movie Show]]''. He also hosted RT\u00c9's live television coverage of ''[[Live 8]] in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]]'', London (July 2005), and ''[[Live Earth]]'' in [[Wembley Stadium]], London (July 2007). He has conducted over 200 interviews with global rock stars.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\"/>\n\nFanning has been the recipient of a number of 'Best DJ' awards from various publications, including ''[[Hot Press]]'' where he topped the annual readers' Poll for over twenty years. In 1980, he was the first person ever outside of RT\u00c9 Radio 1 to be honoured with a prestigious [[Jacob's Awards|Jacob's Award]] for \"the depth and scope\" of his radio show. Following [[Christy Moore]] in 1990 and preceding [[Van Morrison]] in 1992, Fanning was awarded the [[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]] Special Industry Award in 1991. In recent years he has been the recipient of a number of accolades and awards ranging from the 2012 [[Dublin Lord Mayor]]'s Award (\"To the voice of Irish Radio, in recognition of his broadcasting career, his support of new Irish talent and for bringing alternative Irish music to an Irish audience\")<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=Lord Mayor's Award |url=http://www.dublincity.ie/main-menu-services-press-and-news-read-press-release-press-releases-2012-press-releases-april-2012-5 |website=Dublin City}}</ref> to the 2014 [[University College Dublin]] Music Society Award. (The Honorary Fellowship citation reads \"in recognition of his outstanding contribution to music through his work as a journalist, DJ and broadcaster \u2013 in particular his support of homegrown Irish talent\"). He won numerous IRMA awards and was nominated for Best DJ at The [[Meteor Music Awards]] on seven occasions, winning four times. U2 performed a special tribute when he won the Special Industry award in 2004. In 2016, he was inducted into the Irish Radio Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=PPI Hall of Fame |url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2016/0916/816954-ppi-radio-hall-of-fame-dave-fanning-ian-dempsey/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann}}</ref>\n\n''Hot Press'' regards Fanning as \"one of the most familiar faces and voices in Irish broadcasting\",<ref name=\"Dave Fanning, Olaf Tyaransen interview\">{{cite magazine|author=[[Olaf Tyaransen]]|url=http://www.hotpress.com/features/interviews/2646875.html|title=Dave Fanning|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> summing up his impact: \"When Billboard magazine referred to the introduction of 2FM as one of the major factors behind the growth of Ireland as a major music centre, they really meant Dave Fanning\". Rob Sharp of UK newspaper ''[[The Independent]]'' has referred to him as a \"legendary Irish DJ\".<ref name=\"Last Night's Television: Radiohead: The Dave Fanning Interview, Sky Arts 1\"/> [[BP Fallon]] commented in 2008: \"Without Dave Fanning on the radio, music in Ireland would have had a poorer face. Dave changed things, opened up ears\".<ref name=\"Airwaves To Heaven\">{{cite news|author=Padraig Kenny |url=http://www.tribune.ie/article/2008/nov/23/airwaves-to-heaven/ |title=Airwaves To Heaven |date=23 November 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2009 |newspaper=[[Sunday Tribune]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In [[The Sunday Times]] of March 2020, Jim Lockhart said of Fanning \"he was central to a whole generation's interface with music and he is a force of nature\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Jim Lockhart |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jim-lockhart-joining-the-band-was-a-gesture-of-existential-despair-5jkbht3tn |website=The Times |publisher=thetimes.co.uk |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The ''[[Sunday Tribune]]''{{'}}s Eithne Tynan has defined his style as a \"thousand words a minute, start a whole new sentence before you've finished the previous one\".<ref name=\"Radio Review, Eithne Tynan - He doesn't just dress like your grandad, he acts like him too...\">{{cite news|author=Eithne Tynan |url=http://www.tribune.ie/article/2008/dec/14/radio-review-eithne-tynan-he-doesnt-just-dress-lik/ |title=Radio Review, Eithne Tynan \u2013 He doesn't just dress like your grandad, he acts like him too... |date=14 December 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2009 |newspaper=[[Sunday Tribune]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> \n\n==Early and private life==\n\nBorn in [[Dublin]] in 1956, Fanning is the youngest of six children (one sister, four brothers). His father, Barney, was a commissioner in the Irish [[Office of Public Works]], his mother, a retired schoolteacher. Obsessed with music from an early age and fascinated by his older brothers\u2019 music interests (jazz, folk, pop), his twin obsessions, during an \"idyllically happy childhood\" were music and movies. He was a member of [[The Beatles]] fan club from the age of eight. He was educated at [[Blackrock College]],<ref name=\"A celebration of difference united behind a humbling credo\">{{cite news|author=Louise Holden|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/a-celebration-of-difference-united-behind-a-humbling-credo-1.786337|title=A celebration of difference united behind a humbling credo|date=8 December 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|quote='''Comment from Fanning''': \"There were friends all around me throughout my medical life who shared the formation that was Blackrock. The pride in our traditions and accomplishments binds us all and accompanied us through our professional lives. How can we doctors thank you enough, gentle mother?\" '''Comment from fellow student Ryan Tubridy''': \"Late 1960s at Blackrock College: the journalist (Bill Graham), the rock-star big-mouth humanitarian (Bob Smeldof) and the DJ (Fave Danning). Was there something in the water in Williamstown? No. Everything was in the music.\u201d}}</ref> graduating from [[University College, Dublin]] (U.C.D.), with a degree in English and Philosophy and a Higher Diploma in Education. He began working as a DJ on the fledgling pirate radio station, [[Irish pirate radio|Radio Dublin]]; that same year he took over as editor of Ireland's rock magazine (''Scene''). Fanning then moved to Big D when it was formed by Radio Dublin deejays in 1978. On both pirates, he presented rock shows. He continued with that format when he made the move to legal radio in 1979.\n\nHe met [[Gerry Ryan]] in 1978 while both were working in Dublin pirate radio station \"Big D\", sharing the common bond of both having attended college, though at separate colleges.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning: I know there'll never be another like Gerry Ryan\">{{cite news |author=Dave Fanning |url=http://www.herald.ie/opinion/i-know-therell-never-be-another-like-gerry-ryan-27950711.html |title=Dave Fanning: I know there'll never be another like Gerry Ryan |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=1 December 2016 |newspaper=[[The Herald (Ireland)|The Herald]]}}</ref> Their friendship led them to socialise and holiday together, while the Fannings even moved in with the Ryans for a time in September 1995 when the Fanning house was under construction.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning: I know there'll never be another like Gerry Ryan\"/>\n\nHe is married to Ursula, a solicitor (formerly a TV researcher, most notably for [[Gay Byrne]] on ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]''.) and they have three children.\n\n==Career==\nFanning has written for ''[[Hot Press]]'' and ''[[The Irish Times]]'', presented ''[[The Movie Show]]'' and been a disc jockey for [[RT\u00c9 2fm]] since it began in 1979.<ref name=\"At Home With...Dave Fanning\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/2860993.html|title=At Home With...Dave Fanning|date=19 April 2006|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> During the 1990s he worked for RT\u00c9, [[Virgin Radio]] and had four television shows at one point, one of which was ''The Movie Show''.<ref name=\"At Home With...Dave Fanning\"/>\n\n===Radio===\n{{Main|The Dave Fanning Show}}\nHis live sessions, conducted with the assistance of producer Ian Wilson, helped establish him on ''The Rock Show''.<ref name=\"Those who called the tune in Irish music during 2005\">{{cite news |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/archives/2006/0104/ireland/those-who-called-the-tune-in-irish-music-during-2005-834452713.html |title=Those who called the tune in Irish music during 2005 |date=4 January 2006 |accessdate=22 February 2016 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref> However, Joe MacNamee has written in the ''Irish Examiner'' that Wilson was \"the musical heart, soul and brains\" of Fanning's success.<ref name=\"Hats off to Dineen and David Kitt, but no mention for Dave Fanning\">{{cite news|author=Joe McNamee|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2006/01/05/story419256304.asp|title=Hats off to Dineen and David Kitt, but no mention for Dave Fanning|date=5 January 2006|accessdate=21 December 2009|newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]}}{{dead link|date=February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Waterford duo in line for music awards\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/waterfordnews/2006/01/13/story20445.asp |title=Waterford duo in line for music awards |date=13 January 2006 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |publisher=[[Waterford News & Star]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629112652/http://archives.tcm.ie/waterfordnews/2006/01/13/story20445.asp |archivedate=29 June 2011 }}</ref> By the early 1980s, Fanning was seen by the industry and music fans everywhere as Ireland's answer to [[John Peel]], [[BBC Radio 1]] presenter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning/John Peel |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/dave-fanning-s-rock-n-roll-life-1.664751 |work=The Irish Times }}</ref> Alongside [[Larry Gogan]], he is one of only two of the original disc jockeys to make it as far as the station's 40th anniversary in 2019.<ref name=\"Celebrity Diary: Dave Fanning\">{{cite news |first=Dave|last=Fanning|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/celebrity-diary-dave-fanning-27913400.html|title=Celebrity Diary: Dave Fanning|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[Evening Herald]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, after a live TV interview with [[Richard Branson]], Branson invited Fanning to join his new station [[Virgin Radio]]. Fanning presented his own show there every week for two years. With a 4-hour Saturday afternoon programme (following [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]]\u2019 show) broadcast live from London's Soho, Fanning stayed with [[Virgin Radio]] for two years.\n\nIn August 2009, after spending 3 years presenting on [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]], it was announced that Fanning would be returning to [[RT\u00c9 2fm]] to present his evening weekday show in his old 19:00 slot.<ref name=\"Fanning moves back to 2FM\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0818/418511-fanningd/|title=Fanning moves back to 2FM|date=18 August 2009|accessdate=18 August 2009|publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303142125/http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0818/418511-fanningd |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Fanning moves back to 2fm\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/Dave%20Fanning/news/Fanning%20moves%20back%20to%202fm/5737826.html|title=Fanning moves back to 2fm|date=17 August 2009|accessdate=18 August 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Fanning wrote, produced and presented a 6 hour, 6-part radio series for [[BBC Radio 6 Music|BBC 6 Music]] on the history of Irish rock.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC 6 Music |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b042qp5x |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=BBC }}</ref> In the Summer of 2017 he wrote and presented a ten-part [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] series called ''Dave Fanning's History of Irish Rock''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning's History of Irish Rock |url=https://www.rte.ie/radio1/story-of-irish-rock/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 he worked for [[Sirius XM]] Satellite radio in New York.\n\nFanning has been described as \"the ultimate fan, who through broadcasting has been able to make a career out of his many passions in life \u2013 chiefly, music and movies.\" He currently hosts ''[[The Dave Fanning Show]]'', a weekend midday magazine/chat shows on the Irish national radio station [[RTE 2FM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Dave Fanning Show |url=https://2fm.rte.ie/2fm-shows/dave-fanning/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\n===Fanning's Fab Fifty===\nEach year since 1980 Fanning has had an annual alternative music poll called ''Fanning's Fab Fifty'' on his radio show.<ref name=\"Fanning's Fab 50 - vote now for a chance to win music\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/6064528.html|title=Fanning's Fab 50 \u2013 vote now for a chance to win music|date=26 November 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> This is decided by a poll of the general public and, since the advent of internet voting, surfers select their own favourite three pieces of music online.<ref name=\"Fanning's Fab 50 - vote now for a chance to win music\"/> [[U2]] top the poll on a regular basis.<ref name=\"U2 hit is still the One to top Dave's Fab 50\">{{cite news |url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/music/u2-hit-is-still-the-one-to-top-daves-fab-50-27936937.html|title=U2 hit is still the One to top Dave's Fab 50|date=22 December 2009|accessdate=23 December 2009|newspaper=[[Evening Herald]]}}</ref><ref name=\"U2's 'One' Tops Fanning's Fab 50\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/U2/news/U2s-One-Tops-Fannings-Fab-50/6127455.html|title=U2's 'One' Tops Fanning's Fab 50|date=21 December 2009|accessdate=24 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Fanning released an Irish-only triple album, ''Fanning's Fab 50 Vol 1''. Sales for this compilation album reached 1.5 times platinum.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fanning's Fab Fifty |url=http://irishmusicdb.com/compilations/dffabfifty.htm |website=Irish Music Database |publisher=Irish Music Database}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fanning's Fab 50 |url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Dave-Fannings-Fab-50/release/11433032 |publisher=discogs }}</ref> ''Fanning's Fab 50 Vol 2'' was released for the Christmas market in 2006,<ref name=\"My 2006 by Dave Fanning\"/> also going platinum. ''Fanning's Fab 50 Vol 3'' was released in 2007.<ref name=\"deafening\">{{cite web|title=Dave Fanning's Fab 50 ::: Volume 3|url=http://irishmusicdb.com/r/rollerskateskinny/rs_compilations.htm|publisher=Rollerskate Skinny website|accessdate=5 July 2013}}</ref> It includes music pieces by [[U2]], [[The Killers]], [[R.E.M.]], [[Radiohead]], [[Nick Cave]], [[Lou Reed]], [[Massive Attack]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[John Lennon]], [[David Bowie]], [[The Velvet Underground]], [[Coldplay]], [[Sigur R\u00f3s]], [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[Blur (band)|Blur]], [[The Verve]], Ryan Adams, [[The Stone Roses]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] and over thirty others.\n\n===U2===\n\n[[File:Dave and U2 in studio, 1982.jpg|thumb|Dave and U2 in studio, 1982]]\n\nFanning has always supported young, new Irish talent and played bands' demo tapes. With the move to RT\u00c9 Radio 2 ([[RT\u00c9 2FM]]), and with producer Ian Wilson at the helm, they started ''The Fanning Sessions''. Hundreds of sessions were recorded.\n\nFor the very first session, Fanning invited the band he had championed and played most often on demo tape over the previous 2 years \u2013 a young four-piece Dublin band called [[U2]]. His friendship with, and support for, the band, led to Fanning's listeners deciding on the [[A-side and B-side]]s of the band's first single release. (This was in the pre-CD days, when singles were only released on vinyl). The band came into Fanning's show for five nights in one week \u2013 a major seal of approval from Fanning and Wilson \u2013 and the listeners picked \"[[Out of Control (U2 song)|Out of Control]]\" as the first single, with \"[[Stories for Boys]]\" and \"Boy/Girl\" on the B-side.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Three 1979 |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/exhibitions/937-u2/291691-listeners-asked-to-pick-a-side/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\nBetween \u201977 and \u201979, Fanning was resident DJ at Dublin's city center McGonagles nightclub. The club hosted most local acts and many international ones. [[U2]] played there many times. The band also played The Baggot Inn for six consecutive Tuesday nights in 1979 with support from [[The Blades (band)|The Blades]]. Fanning DJ'd for the entire run between sets. He joined the band on their tourbus through Ireland (dates in Cork, Galway, Belfast, Dublin) on the release of their third album ''[[War (U2 album)|War]]''. He made various TV documentaries on the band \u2013 at Self-Aid in \u201986, in [[Modena]] in Italy the following year during the band's ''[[The Joshua Tree Tour|Joshua Tree Tour]]'' and has interviewed the band many times on radio and TV down through the years. In 1987 at the time of the release of [[The Joshua Tree]] his annual radio interview with the band was conducted in the nude following Bono's request to ''\"shake things up for the hell of it\"''.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Interview |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/music-news/rte-dj-dave-fanning-the-day-u2-got-naked-and-drank-beer-in-my-studio-35355645.html |work=The Irish Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Naked on The Dave Fanning Show |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/exhibitions/937-u2/291786-u2-naked/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\nFanning's friendship with the band has continued. At a surprise birthday party, held at Dublin's Mother Redcaps in 1989 all four members of the band paid tribute to Fanning; the band's manager [[Paul McGuinness]] presented him with a special present referring to Fanning as \"the world's best DJ\". Besides being guaranteed the world exclusive on all [[U2]] releases, the band recorded a specially-filmed musical tribute to Fanning when he was presented, in 2004 (by [[Larry Mullen]]) with the Irish Music Industry's top award \u2013 The Meteor Industry Award.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Dave Fanning Tribute |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kEaqWQLj_10 |via=YouTube |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Fanning stepped in for the band at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in Cleveland, Ohio for its weekend celebration of forty years of the band.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 40 |url=https://www.u2.com/news/title/it-was-a-very-nice-kitchen/adam/ |website=U2.com |publisher=U2.com}}</ref>\n\n===Television work===\n{{further|2TV|The Movie Show (Irish TV series)|Planet Rock Profiles|You're a Star}}\n\nOver the past few decades Fanning has fronted over 20 television programmes for Ireland's national television station, [[RT\u00c9]] (these include ''[[2TV]]'', ''[[The Movie Show]]'', ''[[Planet Rock Profiles]]'', ''Jobsuss'', ''The Arts Show'', ''Music Zone'', ''Number One'', ''7 Bands on the Up'', ''What Movie'', ''Visual Eyes''. ''The Last Broadcast'', ''The 11th Hour'' etc.). He has been the subject of various television specials and besides presenting various music shows, both live and recorded, he has presented political TV documentaries from Cambodia and Ethiopia.\n\nThroughout the 1990s, Fanning wrote and presented over four hundred editions of ''[[The Movie Show (Irish TV series)|The Movie Show]]'', crossing the globe for one-on-one interviews with movie stars. The last episode aired in September 2001.<ref name=\"RTE to axe O'Leary talk show at end of January in attempt to cut costs\">{{cite news |author=Conor Keane |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/12/03/story18465.asp |title=RTE to axe O'Leary talk show at end of January in attempt to cut costs |date=3 December 2001 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041230230424/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/12/03/story18465.asp |archivedate=30 December 2004 }}</ref> In 2003 he presented twenty programmes in a series called 'What Movie' and later produced and directed over twenty film review programmes for [[Virgin Media Two|Channel 6]].\n\nFanning has also written and presented over 150 music star TV interview shows which have aired in numerous countries around the world on programmes like ''[[Planet Rock Profiles]]'', ''Music Express'', ''Fanning Profiles'', ''Interviews With Dave Fanning''. In New York for [[AMC Networks|Rainbow Media's]] Rave TV he presented a series of rock star interview programmes in 2006 and 2007<ref name=\"My 2006 by Dave Fanning\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/music/interviews/2901811.html|title=My 2006 by Dave Fanning|date=1 January 2007|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> (programmes included [[Noel Gallagher]], [[Rod Stewart]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[Pet Shop Boys]] etc.). For three years, ''Talks With Dave Fanning'' also ran on [[Sky Arts]] in the UK.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/4154289.html|title=Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky|date=12 October 2007|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]|quote=\"I've done close to 200 interviews for different TV series in the past with the biggest rock stars on the planet, but in terms of production and quality-end product in general, this one is a serious cut above all the others.\"}}</ref> He interviewed [[New Order (band)|New Order]] for the first episode.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\"/> Other episodes featured artists such as [[Beck]], [[The Flaming Lips]], [[Radiohead]]<ref name=\"Last Night's Television: Radiohead: The Dave Fanning Interview, Sky Arts 1\">{{cite news|author=Rob Sharp|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-television-radiohead-the-dave-fanning-interview-sky-arts-1shooting-stars-bbc2-1777663.html|title=Last Night's Television: Radiohead: The Dave Fanning Interview, Sky Arts 1|date=27 August 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> and [[PJ Harvey]].<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\"/>\n\nFor its first four years, Fanning was a member of the panel for the [[Mercury Music Prize]].\n\nIn the early 1990s, he presented live music shows on Britain's [[Channel 4]]. ''Rocksteady'' was filmed from various locations around The UK (from Glasgow's [[Barrowland Ballroom|Barrowlands]] with [[Daniel Lanois]] to London's [[Royal Albert Hall]] with [[Eric Clapton]]), one in Cork with [[Hothouse Flowers]] and one live from Boston with [[J.J. Cale]]. Later (this time with co-presenter [[Craig Ferguson]] and again on [[Channel 4]]) he presented ''Friday at The Dome'', a live music programme from [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]] in London.\n\nWorking with [[Bob Geldof]] (who had been in Gerard Fanning's class in Blackrock College a few years ahead of Dave), Fanning was programme consultant for [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]\u2019s ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' for the music special ''Cool Clear Crystal Streams''.\n\nIn 2004, Fanning caused controversy when he chose to become a judge on television talent show ''[[You're a Star]]'', to choose that year's act to [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest|represent Ireland]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. He explained his decision: <blockquote>It\u2019s indefensible. I just can\u2019t defend this at all. It\u2019s Eurovision for God\u2019s sake. It\u2019s all [[shit]]e, everyone knows that. But I just don't care. I'm doing it for a laugh. Of course I'm going to get people slagging me off, but I'm used to all that. [...] I just thought, why not do it?\" he says. \"I've done everything else at this stage, including the [[Mercury Music Prize]], IMRO Showcases and battle of the bands contests up and down the country. When I did ''[[2TV]]'' from 1995 until 2000 I presided over the worst five years in 50 years of pop music history. It was all [[Boyzone]] videos and I'd slag them all to death. Then they'd be in with me the next week and I'd say 'lads, you're brilliant \u2013 three number ones in a row, well done'. I really like [[Ronan Keating|Ronan]] and [[Keith Duffy|Keith]] as people, they're friends of mine, but I don't like their music. Everyone knows that.<ref name=\"You're A Star - Fanning fights back\">{{cite magazine|author=Colm O'Hare|url=http://www.hotpress.com/features/interviews/2758404.html|title=You're A Star \u2013 Fanning fights back|date=13 October 2004|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn July 2005 he hosted RT\u00c9's 12-hour television coverage of [[Live 8]] from London's [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]] and [[Live Earth]] in 2007 from [[Wembley Stadium]].\n\nIn 2010, Fanning presented a documentary on [[Bono]] (filmed in Ireland and Ghana) for [[RTE]] TV in the ''[[Ireland's Greatest]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ireland's Greatest |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/hume-wins-ireland-s-greatest-award-1.667351 |work=The Irish Times }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 to 2010, Fanning wrote and presented the independently produced, late-night TV music programme ''The Last Broadcast'' (later ''The 11th Hour'') which initially aired on Friday nights and was ninety minutes in length.<ref name=\"Fanning returns to TV\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/2620262.html|title=Fanning returns to TV|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> By 2007, the show aired on Wednesday nights.<ref name=\"Stars come out for Fanning\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/4267601.html|title=Stars come out for Fanning|date=13 November 2007|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]|quote=''Hot Press'' has been making sure to get home early from the pub on Wednesdays to catch the latest and, we reckon, best series of Dave Fanning's ''The Last Broadcast'' yet}}</ref> The show became ''The 11th Hour'' in 2009,<ref name=\"Celebrity Diary: Dave Fanning\"/><ref name=\"Bruce Springsteen and more for Fanning's 11th Hour\"/> with the first episode featuring an interview with [[Bruce Springsteen]] and music from [[Bell X1 (band)|Bell X1]], [[Franz Ferdinand (band)|Franz Ferdinand]] and [[U2]].<ref name=\"Bruce Springsteen and more for Fanning's 11th Hour\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/5298005.html|title=Bruce Springsteen and more for Fanning's 11th Hour|date=11 March 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> Another series followed later in the year, with the first episode on [[The Beatles]] described as \"superb\" by Hilary Fannin, reviewer with ''[[The Irish Times]]''.<ref name=\"Get back: The Beatles v Frank Hall in Fanning's Fab Four fandango\">{{cite news |author=Hilary Fannin|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/the-battle-for-survival-1.758715|title=Get back: The Beatles v Frank Hall in Fanning's Fab Four fandango|date=17 October 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|quote=Dave Fanning is back on the box with a new series of the superb ''The Eleventh Hour'', kicking off with a two-part special on The Beatles, who are draped all over the cooler end of the box these days, given that Abbey Road was number one in the album charts pretty much all over the world exactly 40 years ago.}}</ref>\n\nFanning has contributed to numerous [[BBC]] TV music programmes, most recently [[BBC 4]] TV's ''Pop Roadmap of the 80s'' with [[Midge Ure]] in 2018.\n\nAlso in 2018, Fanning wrote, presented and produced a highly praised TV documentary ''Dolores'', about [[the Cranberries]]' vocalist [[Dolores O'Riordan]], who died in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dolores |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/irish-showbiz/dolores-oriordan-dave-fanning-the-12055764 |work=The Irish Mirror }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning Dolores Documentary |url=https://www.dailyedge.ie/brilliant-response-to-dolores-o-riordan-documentary-on-rte-player-3861260-Feb2018/ |work=The Daily Edge }}</ref>\n\n===Journalism/writing===\n\nFanning has written articles for more than twenty publications, both at home and abroad.  He was rock correspondent with [[The Irish Times]] for ten years (1982 \u2013 1992) and movie critic for the [[Sunday World]] from 1997 to 2004.\n\n[[HarperCollins]] in London approached Fanning to write his autobiography and ''The Thing Is'' was published in 2010. The book's positive ''Irish Times'' review began \"if you were a music loving teenager in the 80s and 90s, you owe a lot to Dave Fanning\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The Thing Is |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/dave-fanning-s-rock-n-roll-life-1.664751 |work=The Irish Times }}</ref> while ''The Independent'' ended its equally positive review with \"that same enthusiasm for music seems to have been undimmed with years and perhaps it's that wisdom ahead of knowledge which has ensured his longevity.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Review: The Thing Is |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/books/review-the-thing-is-by-dave-fanning-26688077.html |newspaper=The Independent }}</ref> Bono wrote the book's lengthy foreword.\n\n===Other work===\n\nIn recent years, Fanning has conducted numerous public interviews with various celebrities and luminaries at numerous events ranging from The [[Dalkey Book Festival]], to Dublin's [[Web Summit]], to The [[Electric Picnic]]. These include, [[Richard E. Grant]] at [[University College Dublin]], [[Jonathan Rhys-Meyers]] in [[Trinity College Dublin]], filmmaker [[David Cronenberg]] at [[Trinity College Dublin]], Glastonbury's [[Michael Eavis]] at the [[Aviva Stadium]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning Bestin Fest |url=https://bestinfest.ie/ |website=bestinfest |publisher=bestinfest.ie |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>, Sopranos creator [[David Chase]] at the residence of the American Ambassador in Dublin's [[Phoenix Park]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning David Chase |url=https://ie.usembassy.gov/tag/david-chase/ |website=usembassy |publisher=ie.usembassy.gov |accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> [[Billie Eilish]] at [[Electric Picnic]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning Interviews Billie Eilish |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e29uIWsfnn0 |via=YouTube |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> etc. \n\nFanning wrote the sleeve notes for Ireland's first ever rock compilation album ''Just For Kicks''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ireland's First Rock Compilation Album |url=https://www.irishrock.org/comps/justforkicks.html |website=irishrock |publisher=irishrock.org |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nFanning has been a stage announcer at most major music festivals and large concerts in Ireland dating back to [[Bob Marley and The Wailers]] at Dalymount Park in 1980 and [[Thin Lizzy]]/[[U2]] at the very first [[Slane Castle|Slane]] concert in 1981.\n\nFor its first four years, Fanning was a member of the panel for the [[Mercury Music Prize]].\n\nFrom 2009 to 2013, he hosted the 10th [[Kerry Film Festival]] in [[Tralee]].<ref name=\"Stars descend for Film Festival\">{{cite news |author=Simon Brouder |url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/kerryman/news/stars-descend-for-film-festival-27388643.html |title=Stars descend for Film Festival |date=11 November 2009 |accessdate=20 December 2009 |newspaper=[[The Kerryman]]'}}</ref>\n\nFanning is parodied by [[Oliver Callan]].<ref name=\"Gift Grub stars in stand-up row over new CD money\">{{cite news |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/gift-grub-stars-in-stand-up-row-over-new-cd-money-17525.html |title=Gift Grub stars in stand-up row over new CD money |date=6 November 2006 |accessdate=22 February 2015 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]] }}</ref>\n\nHis contributions were featured in both of the big-screen documentary films of [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] and [[Coldplay]] \u2013 ''[[Oasis: Supersonic]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Oasis: Supersonic |url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/oasis-acknowledge-irish-roots-in-new-documentary-18723050 |work=Hot Press |accessdate=2016\u20132017}}</ref> in 2016 and ''[[Coldplay: A Head Full of Dreams]]'' in 2018.\n\n==Awards==\nFanning has been the recipient of a number of 'Best DJ' awards from various publications, including [[Hot Press]] where he topped the annual Readers' Poll for over twenty years. In 1980, he was the first person ever outside of [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] to be honoured with a prestigious [[Jacob's Awards|Jacob's Award]] for \"the depth and scope\" of his radio show. Following [[Christy Moore]] in 1990 and preceding [[Van Morrison]] in 1992, Fanning was awarded the [[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]] Special Industry Award in 1991. In recent years he's been the recipient of a number of accolades and awards ranging from the 2012 [[Dublin Lord Mayor]]\u2019s Award (\"To the voice of Irish Radio, in recognition of his broadcasting career, his support of new Irish talent and for bringing alternative Irish music to an Irish audience\")<ref name=\"auto\"/> to the 2014 [[University College Dublin]] Music Society Award. (The Honorary Fellowship citation reads \"in recognition of his outstanding contribution to music through his work as a journalist, DJ and broadcaster \u2013 in particular his support of homegrown Irish talent\"). He won numerous IRMA awards and was nominated for Best DJ at The [[Meteor Music Awards]] on seven occasions, winning four times. U2 performed a special tribute when he won the Special Industry award in 2004. In 2016, he was inducted into the Irish Radio Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| [[2004 Meteor Awards|2004]] || Dave Fanning || Industry Award || {{won}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2fm}}\n{{RTER1}}\n{{U2}}\n{{You're a Star}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fanning, Dave}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Irish DJs]]\n[[Category:Irish film critics]]\n[[Category:Irish music journalists]]\n[[Category:Irish television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Jacob's Award winners]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 Radio 1 presenters]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 2fm presenters]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 television presenters]]\n[[Category:People educated at Blackrock College]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people||David Fanning (disambiguation)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Dave Fanning\n|image         = Dave Fanning 2015 (cropped).jpg\n|image_size    =\n|caption       = Dave Fanning at 2015 Web Summit Music Stage\n|birth_name    = David Fanning\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1956|02|27|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Dublin]], Ireland\n|death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} -->\n|death_place   =\n|body_discovered =\n|death_cause   =\n|resting_place =\n|resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} -->\n|residence     =\n|nationality   = Irish\n|citizenship   =\n|other_names   =\n|known_for     = Music industry work, friendship with [[U2]], ''Fanning's Fab 50''\n|education     = English and Philosophy degree/Higher Diploma in Education\n|alma_mater    = [[University College, Dublin]]\n|employer      = [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]]\n|occupation    = Radio and television presenter\n|years_active  =\n|home_town     =\n|title         =\n|salary        =\n|networth      =\n|height        =\n|weight        =\n|term          =\n|predecessor   =\n|successor     =\n|party         =\n|opponents     =\n|boards        =\n|religion      =\n|spouse        = Ursula Courtney\n|partner       =\n|children      = Jack, Robert and Hayley\n|parents       =\n|relations     =\n|callsign      =\n|signature     =\n|website       =\n|footnotes     =\n}}\n'''David Fanning''' (born 27 February 1956) is an Irish television and radio broadcaster, rock journalist, DJ, film critic and author. Fanning currently hosts weekend midday magazine/chat show ''[[The Dave Fanning Show]]'' on the Irish national radio station [[RT\u00c9 2fm]] and a number of [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] programmes. He regularly deputises on RT\u00c9 Radio 1 across a range of primetime programmes and also presented his own Monday-Friday 9&nbsp;am show ''Mornings With Dave Fanning'' in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mornings with Dave Fanning |url=https://www.rte.ie/radio1/the-john-murray-show/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann}}</ref>\n\nDue to his friendship with [[U2]], Fanning has for four decades been granted the first airing of any of the band's new singles before anyone else in the world,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0116/415914-u2/|title=World premiere for new U2 on RT\u00c9 2fm|date=16 January 2009|accessdate=16 January 2009|publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303134318/http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0116/415914-u2/ |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> with band members often calling Fanning to tell him what they are doing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/8469694.stm|title=U2 and Jay-Z record song for Haiti|date=20 January 2010|accessdate=24 January 2010|publisher=BBC}}</ref> He has presented more than twenty different TV shows for [[RT\u00c9 Television]], from ''[[2TV]]'' to ''[[The Movie Show (Irish TV series)|The Movie Show]]''. He also hosted RT\u00c9's live television coverage of ''[[Live 8]] in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]]'', London (July 2005), and ''[[Live Earth]]'' in [[Wembley Stadium]], London (July 2007). He has conducted over 200 interviews with global rock stars.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\"/>\n\nFanning has been the recipient of a number of 'Best DJ' awards from various publications, including ''[[Hot Press]]'' where he topped the annual readers' Poll for over twenty years. In 1980, he was the first person ever outside of RT\u00c9 Radio 1 to be honoured with a prestigious [[Jacob's Awards|Jacob's Award]] for \"the depth and scope\" of his radio show. Following [[Christy Moore]] in 1990 and preceding [[Van Morrison]] in 1992, Fanning was awarded the [[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]] Special Industry Award in 1991. In recent years he has been the recipient of a number of accolades and awards ranging from the 2012 [[Dublin Lord Mayor]]'s Award (\"To the voice of Irish Radio, in recognition of his broadcasting career, his support of new Irish talent and for bringing alternative Irish music to an Irish audience\")<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=Lord Mayor's Award |url=http://www.dublincity.ie/main-menu-services-press-and-news-read-press-release-press-releases-2012-press-releases-april-2012-5 |website=Dublin City}}</ref> to the 2014 [[University College Dublin]] Music Society Award. (The Honorary Fellowship citation reads \"in recognition of his outstanding contribution to music through his work as a journalist, DJ and broadcaster \u2013 in particular his support of homegrown Irish talent\"). He won numerous IRMA awards and was nominated for Best DJ at The [[Meteor Music Awards]] on seven occasions, winning four times. U2 performed a special tribute when he won the Special Industry award in 2004. In 2016, he was inducted into the Irish Radio Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=PPI Hall of Fame |url=https://www.rte.ie/entertainment/2016/0916/816954-ppi-radio-hall-of-fame-dave-fanning-ian-dempsey/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann}}</ref>\n\n''Hot Press'' regards Fanning as \"one of the most familiar faces and voices in Irish broadcasting\",<ref name=\"Dave Fanning, Olaf Tyaransen interview\">{{cite magazine|author=[[Olaf Tyaransen]]|url=http://www.hotpress.com/features/interviews/2646875.html|title=Dave Fanning|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> summing up his impact: \"When Billboard magazine referred to the introduction of 2FM as one of the major factors behind the growth of Ireland as a major music centre, they really meant Dave Fanning\". Rob Sharp of UK newspaper ''[[The Independent]]'' has referred to him as a \"legendary Irish DJ\".<ref name=\"Last Night's Television: Radiohead: The Dave Fanning Interview, Sky Arts 1\"/> [[BP Fallon]] commented in 2008: \"Without Dave Fanning on the radio, music in Ireland would have had a poorer face. Dave changed things, opened up ears\".<ref name=\"Airwaves To Heaven\">{{cite news|author=Padraig Kenny |url=http://www.tribune.ie/article/2008/nov/23/airwaves-to-heaven/ |title=Airwaves To Heaven |date=23 November 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2009 |newspaper=[[Sunday Tribune]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In [[The Sunday Times]] of March 2020, Jim Lockhart said of Fanning \"he was central to a whole generation's interface with music and he is a force of nature\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Jim Lockhart |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/jim-lockhart-joining-the-band-was-a-gesture-of-existential-despair-5jkbht3tn |website=The Times |publisher=thetimes.co.uk |accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The ''[[Sunday Tribune]]''{{'}}s Eithne Tynan has defined his style as a \"thousand words a minute, start a whole new sentence before you've finished the previous one\".<ref name=\"Radio Review, Eithne Tynan - He doesn't just dress like your grandad, he acts like him too...\">{{cite news|author=Eithne Tynan |url=http://www.tribune.ie/article/2008/dec/14/radio-review-eithne-tynan-he-doesnt-just-dress-lik/ |title=Radio Review, Eithne Tynan \u2013 He doesn't just dress like your grandad, he acts like him too... |date=14 December 2008 |accessdate=20 December 2009 |newspaper=[[Sunday Tribune]] }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> \n\n==Early and private life==\n\nBorn in [[Dublin]] in 1956, Fanning is the youngest of six children (one sister, four brothers). His father, Barney, was a commissioner in the Irish [[Office of Public Works]], his mother, a retired schoolteacher. Obsessed with music from an early age and fascinated by his older brothers\u2019 music interests (jazz, folk, pop), his twin obsessions, during an \"idyllically happy childhood\" were music and movies. He was a member of [[The Beatles]] fan club from the age of eight. He was educated at [[Blackrock College]],<ref name=\"A celebration of difference united behind a humbling credo\">{{cite news|author=Louise Holden|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/a-celebration-of-difference-united-behind-a-humbling-credo-1.786337|title=A celebration of difference united behind a humbling credo|date=8 December 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|quote='''Comment from Fanning''': \"There were friends all around me throughout my medical life who shared the formation that was Blackrock. The pride in our traditions and accomplishments binds us all and accompanied us through our professional lives. How can we doctors thank you enough, gentle mother?\" '''Comment from fellow student Ryan Tubridy''': \"Late 1960s at Blackrock College: the journalist (Bill Graham), the rock-star big-mouth humanitarian (Bob Smeldof) and the DJ (Fave Danning). Was there something in the water in Williamstown? No. Everything was in the music.\u201d}}</ref> graduating from [[University College, Dublin]] (U.C.D.), with a degree in English and Philosophy and a Higher Diploma in Education. He began working as a DJ on the fledgling pirate radio station, [[Irish pirate radio|Radio Dublin]]; that same year he took over as editor of Ireland's rock magazine (''Scene''). Fanning then moved to Big D when it was formed by Radio Dublin deejays in 1978. On both pirates, he presented rock shows. He continued with that format when he made the move to legal radio in 1979.\n\nHe met [[Gerry Ryan]] in 1978 while both were working in Dublin pirate radio station \"Big D\", sharing the common bond of both having attended college, though at separate colleges.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning: I know there'll never be another like Gerry Ryan\">{{cite news |author=Dave Fanning |url=http://www.herald.ie/opinion/i-know-therell-never-be-another-like-gerry-ryan-27950711.html |title=Dave Fanning: I know there'll never be another like Gerry Ryan |date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=1 December 2016 |newspaper=[[The Herald (Ireland)|The Herald]]}}</ref> Their friendship led them to socialise and holiday together, while the Fannings even moved in with the Ryans for a time in September 1995 when the Fanning house was under construction.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning: I know there'll never be another like Gerry Ryan\"/>\n\nHe is married to Ursula, a solicitor (formerly a TV researcher, most notably for [[Gay Byrne]] on ''[[The Late Late Show (Ireland)|The Late Late Show]]''.) and they have three children.\n\n==Career==\nFanning has written for ''[[Hot Press]]'' and ''[[The Irish Times]]'', presented ''[[The Movie Show]]'' and been a disc jockey for [[RT\u00c9 2fm]] since it began in 1979.<ref name=\"At Home With...Dave Fanning\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/archive/2860993.html|title=At Home With...Dave Fanning|date=19 April 2006|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> During the 1990s he worked for RT\u00c9, [[Virgin Radio]] and had four television shows at one point, one of which was ''The Movie Show''.<ref name=\"At Home With...Dave Fanning\"/>\n\n===Radio===\n{{Main|The Dave Fanning Show}}\nHis live sessions, conducted with the assistance of producer Ian Wilson, helped establish him on ''The Rock Show''.<ref name=\"Those who called the tune in Irish music during 2005\">{{cite news |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/archives/2006/0104/ireland/those-who-called-the-tune-in-irish-music-during-2005-834452713.html |title=Those who called the tune in Irish music during 2005 |date=4 January 2006 |accessdate=22 February 2016 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref> However, Joe MacNamee has written in the ''Irish Examiner'' that Wilson was \"the musical heart, soul and brains\" of Fanning's success.<ref name=\"Hats off to Dineen and David Kitt, but no mention for Dave Fanning\">{{cite news|author=Joe McNamee|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2006/01/05/story419256304.asp|title=Hats off to Dineen and David Kitt, but no mention for Dave Fanning|date=5 January 2006|accessdate=21 December 2009|newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]}}{{dead link|date=February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Waterford duo in line for music awards\">{{cite news|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/waterfordnews/2006/01/13/story20445.asp |title=Waterford duo in line for music awards |date=13 January 2006 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |publisher=[[Waterford News & Star]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629112652/http://archives.tcm.ie/waterfordnews/2006/01/13/story20445.asp |archivedate=29 June 2011 }}</ref> By the early 1980s, Fanning was seen by the industry and music fans everywhere as Ireland's answer to [[John Peel]], [[BBC Radio 1]] presenter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning/John Peel |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/dave-fanning-s-rock-n-roll-life-1.664751 |work=The Irish Times }}</ref> Alongside [[Larry Gogan]], he is one of only two of the original disc jockeys to make it as far as the station's 40th anniversary in 2019.<ref name=\"Celebrity Diary: Dave Fanning\">{{cite news |first=Dave|last=Fanning|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/around-town/celebrity-diary-dave-fanning-27913400.html|title=Celebrity Diary: Dave Fanning|date=29 May 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[Evening Herald]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, after a live TV interview with [[Richard Branson]], Branson invited Fanning to join his new station [[Virgin Radio]]. Fanning presented his own show there every week for two years. With a 4-hour Saturday afternoon programme (following [[Chris Evans (presenter)|Chris Evans]]\u2019 show) broadcast live from London's Soho, Fanning stayed with [[Virgin Radio]] for two years.\n\nIn August 2009, after spending 3 years presenting on [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]], it was announced that Fanning would be returning to [[RT\u00c9 2fm]] to present his evening weekday show in his old 19:00 slot.<ref name=\"Fanning moves back to 2FM\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0818/418511-fanningd/|title=Fanning moves back to 2FM|date=18 August 2009|accessdate=18 August 2009|publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303142125/http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2009/0818/418511-fanningd |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Fanning moves back to 2fm\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/Dave%20Fanning/news/Fanning%20moves%20back%20to%202fm/5737826.html|title=Fanning moves back to 2fm|date=17 August 2009|accessdate=18 August 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Fanning wrote, produced and presented a 6 hour, 6-part radio series for [[BBC Radio 6 Music|BBC 6 Music]] on the history of Irish rock.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC 6 Music |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b042qp5x |website=BBC.co.uk |publisher=BBC }}</ref> In the Summer of 2017 he wrote and presented a ten-part [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] series called ''Dave Fanning's History of Irish Rock''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning's History of Irish Rock |url=https://www.rte.ie/radio1/story-of-irish-rock/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 he worked for [[Sirius XM]] Satellite radio in New York.\n\nFanning has been described as \"the ultimate fan, who through broadcasting has been able to make a career out of his many passions in life \u2013 chiefly, music and movies.\" He currently hosts ''[[The Dave Fanning Show]]'', a weekend midday magazine/chat shows on the Irish national radio station [[RTE 2FM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=The Dave Fanning Show |url=https://2fm.rte.ie/2fm-shows/dave-fanning/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\n===Fanning's Fab Fifty===\nEach year since 1980 Fanning has had an annual alternative music poll called ''Fanning's Fab Fifty'' on his radio show.<ref name=\"Fanning's Fab 50 - vote now for a chance to win music\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/6064528.html|title=Fanning's Fab 50 \u2013 vote now for a chance to win music|date=26 November 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> This is decided by a poll of the general public and, since the advent of internet voting, surfers select their own favourite three pieces of music online.<ref name=\"Fanning's Fab 50 - vote now for a chance to win music\"/> [[U2]] top the poll on a regular basis.<ref name=\"U2 hit is still the One to top Dave's Fab 50\">{{cite news |url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/music/u2-hit-is-still-the-one-to-top-daves-fab-50-27936937.html|title=U2 hit is still the One to top Dave's Fab 50|date=22 December 2009|accessdate=23 December 2009|newspaper=[[Evening Herald]]}}</ref><ref name=\"U2's 'One' Tops Fanning's Fab 50\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/U2/news/U2s-One-Tops-Fannings-Fab-50/6127455.html|title=U2's 'One' Tops Fanning's Fab 50|date=21 December 2009|accessdate=24 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Fanning released an Irish-only triple album, ''Fanning's Fab 50 Vol 1''. Sales for this compilation album reached 1.5 times platinum.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fanning's Fab Fifty |url=http://irishmusicdb.com/compilations/dffabfifty.htm |website=Irish Music Database |publisher=Irish Music Database}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Fanning's Fab 50 |url=https://www.discogs.com/Various-Dave-Fannings-Fab-50/release/11433032 |publisher=discogs }}</ref> ''Fanning's Fab 50 Vol 2'' was released for the Christmas market in 2006,<ref name=\"My 2006 by Dave Fanning\"/> also going platinum. ''Fanning's Fab 50 Vol 3'' was released in 2007.<ref name=\"deafening\">{{cite web|title=Dave Fanning's Fab 50 ::: Volume 3|url=http://irishmusicdb.com/r/rollerskateskinny/rs_compilations.htm|publisher=Rollerskate Skinny website|accessdate=5 July 2013}}</ref> It includes music pieces by [[U2]], [[The Killers]], [[R.E.M.]], [[Radiohead]], [[Nick Cave]], [[Lou Reed]], [[Massive Attack]], [[Paul McCartney]], [[John Lennon]], [[David Bowie]], [[The Velvet Underground]], [[Coldplay]], [[Sigur R\u00f3s]], [[New Order (band)|New Order]], [[Blur (band)|Blur]], [[The Verve]], Ryan Adams, [[The Stone Roses]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] and over thirty others.\n\n===U2===\nFanning has always supported young, new Irish talent and played bands' demo tapes. With the move to RT\u00c9 Radio 2 ([[RT\u00c9 2FM]]), and with producer Ian Wilson at the helm, they started ''The Fanning Sessions''. Hundreds of sessions were recorded.\n\nFor the very first session, Fanning invited the band he had championed and played most often on demo tape over the previous 2 years \u2013 a young four-piece Dublin band called [[U2]]. His friendship with, and support for, the band, led to Fanning's listeners deciding on the [[A-side and B-side]]s of the band's first single release. (This was in the pre-CD days, when singles were only released on vinyl). The band came into Fanning's show for five nights in one week \u2013 a major seal of approval from Fanning and Wilson \u2013 and the listeners picked \"[[Out of Control (U2 song)|Out of Control]]\" as the first single, with \"[[Stories for Boys]]\" and \"Boy/Girl\" on the B-side.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Three 1979 |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/exhibitions/937-u2/291691-listeners-asked-to-pick-a-side/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\nBetween \u201977 and \u201979, Fanning was resident DJ at Dublin's city center McGonagles nightclub. The club hosted most local acts and many international ones. [[U2]] played there many times. The band also played The Baggot Inn for six consecutive Tuesday nights in 1979 with support from [[The Blades (band)|The Blades]]. Fanning DJ'd for the entire run between sets. He joined the band on their tourbus through Ireland (dates in Cork, Galway, Belfast, Dublin) on the release of their third album ''[[War (U2 album)|War]]''. He made various TV documentaries on the band \u2013 at Self-Aid in \u201986, in [[Modena]] in Italy the following year during the band's ''[[The Joshua Tree Tour|Joshua Tree Tour]]'' and has interviewed the band many times on radio and TV down through the years. In 1987 at the time of the release of [[The Joshua Tree]] his annual radio interview with the band was conducted in the nude following Bono's request to ''\"shake things up for the hell of it\"''.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Interview |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/music/music-news/rte-dj-dave-fanning-the-day-u2-got-naked-and-drank-beer-in-my-studio-35355645.html |work=The Irish Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Naked on The Dave Fanning Show |url=https://www.rte.ie/archives/exhibitions/937-u2/291786-u2-naked/ |publisher=Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann }}</ref>\n\nFanning's friendship with the band has continued. At a surprise birthday party, held at Dublin's Mother Redcaps in 1989 all four members of the band paid tribute to Fanning; the band's manager [[Paul McGuinness]] presented him with a special present referring to Fanning as \"the world's best DJ\". Besides being guaranteed the world exclusive on all [[U2]] releases, the band recorded a specially-filmed musical tribute to Fanning when he was presented, in 2004 (by [[Larry Mullen]]) with the Irish Music Industry's top award \u2013 The Meteor Industry Award.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 Dave Fanning Tribute |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kEaqWQLj_10 |via=YouTube |accessdate=10 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Fanning stepped in for the band at the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in Cleveland, Ohio for its weekend celebration of forty years of the band.<ref>{{cite web |title=U2 40 |url=https://www.u2.com/news/title/it-was-a-very-nice-kitchen/adam/ |website=U2.com |publisher=U2.com}}</ref>\n\n===Television work===\n{{further|2TV|The Movie Show (Irish TV series)|Planet Rock Profiles|You're a Star}}\n\nOver the past few decades Fanning has fronted over 20 television programmes for Ireland's national television station, [[RT\u00c9]] (these include ''[[2TV]]'', ''[[The Movie Show]]'', ''[[Planet Rock Profiles]]'', ''Jobsuss'', ''The Arts Show'', ''Music Zone'', ''Number One'', ''7 Bands on the Up'', ''What Movie'', ''Visual Eyes''. ''The Last Broadcast'', ''The 11th Hour'' etc.). He has been the subject of various television specials and besides presenting various music shows, both live and recorded, he has presented political TV documentaries from Cambodia and Ethiopia.\n\nThroughout the 1990s, Fanning wrote and presented over four hundred editions of ''[[The Movie Show (Irish TV series)|The Movie Show]]'', crossing the globe for one-on-one interviews with movie stars. The last episode aired in September 2001.<ref name=\"RTE to axe O'Leary talk show at end of January in attempt to cut costs\">{{cite news |author=Conor Keane |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/12/03/story18465.asp |title=RTE to axe O'Leary talk show at end of January in attempt to cut costs |date=3 December 2001 |accessdate=21 December 2009 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041230230424/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2001/12/03/story18465.asp |archivedate=30 December 2004 }}</ref> In 2003 he presented twenty programmes in a series called 'What Movie' and later produced and directed over twenty film review programmes for [[Virgin Media Two|Channel 6]].\n\nFanning has also written and presented over 150 music star TV interview shows which have aired in numerous countries around the world on programmes like ''[[Planet Rock Profiles]]'', ''Music Express'', ''Fanning Profiles'', ''Interviews With Dave Fanning''. In New York for [[AMC Networks|Rainbow Media's]] Rave TV he presented a series of rock star interview programmes in 2006 and 2007<ref name=\"My 2006 by Dave Fanning\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/music/interviews/2901811.html|title=My 2006 by Dave Fanning|date=1 January 2007|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> (programmes included [[Noel Gallagher]], [[Rod Stewart]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[Pet Shop Boys]] etc.). For three years, ''Talks With Dave Fanning'' also ran on [[Sky Arts]] in the UK.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/4154289.html|title=Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky|date=12 October 2007|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]|quote=\"I've done close to 200 interviews for different TV series in the past with the biggest rock stars on the planet, but in terms of production and quality-end product in general, this one is a serious cut above all the others.\"}}</ref> He interviewed [[New Order (band)|New Order]] for the first episode.<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\"/> Other episodes featured artists such as [[Beck]], [[The Flaming Lips]], [[Radiohead]]<ref name=\"Last Night's Television: Radiohead: The Dave Fanning Interview, Sky Arts 1\">{{cite news|author=Rob Sharp|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/last-nights-television-radiohead-the-dave-fanning-interview-sky-arts-1shooting-stars-bbc2-1777663.html|title=Last Night's Television: Radiohead: The Dave Fanning Interview, Sky Arts 1|date=27 August 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> and [[PJ Harvey]].<ref name=\"Dave Fanning to present new show on Sky\"/>\n\nFor its first four years, Fanning was a member of the panel for the [[Mercury Music Prize]].\n\nIn the early 1990s, he presented live music shows on Britain's [[Channel 4]]. ''Rocksteady'' was filmed from various locations around The UK (from Glasgow's [[Barrowland Ballroom|Barrowlands]] with [[Daniel Lanois]] to London's [[Royal Albert Hall]] with [[Eric Clapton]]), one in Cork with [[Hothouse Flowers]] and one live from Boston with [[J.J. Cale]]. Later (this time with co-presenter [[Craig Ferguson]] and again on [[Channel 4]]) he presented ''Friday at The Dome'', a live music programme from [[Kilburn, London|Kilburn]] in London.\n\nWorking with [[Bob Geldof]] (who had been in Gerard Fanning's class in Blackrock College a few years ahead of Dave), Fanning was programme consultant for [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]]\u2019s ''[[The South Bank Show]]'' for the music special ''Cool Clear Crystal Streams''.\n\nIn 2004, Fanning caused controversy when he chose to become a judge on television talent show ''[[You're a Star]]'', to choose that year's act to [[Ireland in the Eurovision Song Contest|represent Ireland]] in the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]. He explained his decision: <blockquote>It\u2019s indefensible. I just can\u2019t defend this at all. It\u2019s Eurovision for God\u2019s sake. It\u2019s all [[shit]]e, everyone knows that. But I just don't care. I'm doing it for a laugh. Of course I'm going to get people slagging me off, but I'm used to all that. [...] I just thought, why not do it?\" he says. \"I've done everything else at this stage, including the [[Mercury Music Prize]], IMRO Showcases and battle of the bands contests up and down the country. When I did ''[[2TV]]'' from 1995 until 2000 I presided over the worst five years in 50 years of pop music history. It was all [[Boyzone]] videos and I'd slag them all to death. Then they'd be in with me the next week and I'd say 'lads, you're brilliant \u2013 three number ones in a row, well done'. I really like [[Ronan Keating|Ronan]] and [[Keith Duffy|Keith]] as people, they're friends of mine, but I don't like their music. Everyone knows that.<ref name=\"You're A Star - Fanning fights back\">{{cite magazine|author=Colm O'Hare|url=http://www.hotpress.com/features/interviews/2758404.html|title=You're A Star \u2013 Fanning fights back|date=13 October 2004|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nIn July 2005 he hosted RT\u00c9's 12-hour television coverage of [[Live 8]] from London's [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]] and [[Live Earth]] in 2007 from [[Wembley Stadium]].\n\nIn 2010, Fanning presented a documentary on [[Bono]] (filmed in Ireland and Ghana) for [[RTE]] TV in the ''[[Ireland's Greatest]]'' series.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ireland's Greatest |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/hume-wins-ireland-s-greatest-award-1.667351 |work=The Irish Times }}</ref>\n\nFrom 2000 to 2010, Fanning wrote and presented the independently produced, late-night TV music programme ''The Last Broadcast'' (later ''The 11th Hour'') which initially aired on Friday nights and was ninety minutes in length.<ref name=\"Fanning returns to TV\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/2620262.html|title=Fanning returns to TV|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> By 2007, the show aired on Wednesday nights.<ref name=\"Stars come out for Fanning\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/4267601.html|title=Stars come out for Fanning|date=13 November 2007|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]|quote=''Hot Press'' has been making sure to get home early from the pub on Wednesdays to catch the latest and, we reckon, best series of Dave Fanning's ''The Last Broadcast'' yet}}</ref> The show became ''The 11th Hour'' in 2009,<ref name=\"Celebrity Diary: Dave Fanning\"/><ref name=\"Bruce Springsteen and more for Fanning's 11th Hour\"/> with the first episode featuring an interview with [[Bruce Springsteen]] and music from [[Bell X1 (band)|Bell X1]], [[Franz Ferdinand (band)|Franz Ferdinand]] and [[U2]].<ref name=\"Bruce Springsteen and more for Fanning's 11th Hour\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hotpress.com/news/5298005.html|title=Bruce Springsteen and more for Fanning's 11th Hour|date=11 March 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|magazine=[[Hot Press]]}}</ref> Another series followed later in the year, with the first episode on [[The Beatles]] described as \"superb\" by Hilary Fannin, reviewer with ''[[The Irish Times]]''.<ref name=\"Get back: The Beatles v Frank Hall in Fanning's Fab Four fandango\">{{cite news |author=Hilary Fannin|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/the-battle-for-survival-1.758715|title=Get back: The Beatles v Frank Hall in Fanning's Fab Four fandango|date=17 October 2009|accessdate=20 December 2009|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]|quote=Dave Fanning is back on the box with a new series of the superb ''The Eleventh Hour'', kicking off with a two-part special on The Beatles, who are draped all over the cooler end of the box these days, given that Abbey Road was number one in the album charts pretty much all over the world exactly 40 years ago.}}</ref>\n\nFanning has contributed to numerous [[BBC]] TV music programmes, most recently [[BBC 4]] TV's ''Pop Roadmap of the 80s'' with [[Midge Ure]] in 2018.\n\nAlso in 2018, Fanning wrote, presented and produced a highly praised TV documentary ''Dolores'', about [[the Cranberries]]' vocalist [[Dolores O'Riordan]], who died in January 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dolores |url=https://www.irishmirror.ie/showbiz/irish-showbiz/dolores-oriordan-dave-fanning-the-12055764 |work=The Irish Mirror }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning Dolores Documentary |url=https://www.dailyedge.ie/brilliant-response-to-dolores-o-riordan-documentary-on-rte-player-3861260-Feb2018/ |work=The Daily Edge }}</ref>\n\n===Journalism/writing===\n\nFanning has written articles for more than twenty publications, both at home and abroad.  He was rock correspondent with [[The Irish Times]] for ten years (1982 \u2013 1992) and movie critic for the [[Sunday World]] from 1997 to 2004.\n\n[[HarperCollins]] in London approached Fanning to write his autobiography and ''The Thing Is'' was published in 2010. The book's positive ''Irish Times'' review began \"if you were a music loving teenager in the 80s and 90s, you owe a lot to Dave Fanning\"<ref>{{cite web |title=The Thing Is |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/books/dave-fanning-s-rock-n-roll-life-1.664751 |work=The Irish Times }}</ref> while ''The Independent'' ended its equally positive review with \"that same enthusiasm for music seems to have been undimmed with years and perhaps it's that wisdom ahead of knowledge which has ensured his longevity.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Review: The Thing Is |url=https://www.independent.ie/entertainment/books/review-the-thing-is-by-dave-fanning-26688077.html |newspaper=The Independent }}</ref> Bono wrote the book's lengthy foreword.\n\n===Other work===\n\nIn recent years, Fanning has conducted numerous public interviews with various celebrities and luminaries at numerous events ranging from The [[Dalkey Book Festival]], to Dublin's [[Web Summit]], to The [[Electric Picnic]]. These include, [[Richard E. Grant]] at [[University College Dublin]], [[Jonathan Rhys-Meyers]] in [[Trinity College Dublin]], filmmaker [[David Cronenberg]] at [[Trinity College Dublin]], Glastonbury's [[Michael Eavis]] at the [[Aviva Stadium]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning Bestin Fest |url=https://bestinfest.ie/ |website=bestinfest |publisher=bestinfest.ie |accessdate=1 June 2016}}</ref>, Sopranos creator [[David Chase]] at the residence of the American Ambassador in Dublin's [[Phoenix Park]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning David Chase |url=https://ie.usembassy.gov/tag/david-chase/ |website=usembassy |publisher=ie.usembassy.gov |accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> [[Billie Eilish]] at [[Electric Picnic]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Dave Fanning Interviews Billie Eilish |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e29uIWsfnn0 |via=YouTube |accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref> etc. \n\nFanning wrote the sleeve notes for Ireland's first ever rock compilation album ''Just For Kicks''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ireland's First Rock Compilation Album |url=https://www.irishrock.org/comps/justforkicks.html |website=irishrock |publisher=irishrock.org |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nFanning has been a stage announcer at most major music festivals and large concerts in Ireland dating back to [[Bob Marley and The Wailers]] at Dalymount Park in 1980 and [[Thin Lizzy]]/[[U2]] at the very first [[Slane Castle|Slane]] concert in 1981.\n\nFor its first four years, Fanning was a member of the panel for the [[Mercury Music Prize]].\n\nFrom 2009 to 2013, he hosted the 10th [[Kerry Film Festival]] in [[Tralee]].<ref name=\"Stars descend for Film Festival\">{{cite news |author=Simon Brouder |url=http://www.independent.ie/regionals/kerryman/news/stars-descend-for-film-festival-27388643.html |title=Stars descend for Film Festival |date=11 November 2009 |accessdate=20 December 2009 |newspaper=[[The Kerryman]]'}}</ref>\n\nFanning is parodied by [[Oliver Callan]].<ref name=\"Gift Grub stars in stand-up row over new CD money\">{{cite news |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/gift-grub-stars-in-stand-up-row-over-new-cd-money-17525.html |title=Gift Grub stars in stand-up row over new CD money |date=6 November 2006 |accessdate=22 February 2015 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]] }}</ref>\n\nHis contributions were featured in both of the big-screen documentary films of [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] and [[Coldplay]] \u2013 ''[[Oasis: Supersonic]]''<ref>{{cite web |title=Oasis: Supersonic |url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/oasis-acknowledge-irish-roots-in-new-documentary-18723050 |work=Hot Press |accessdate=2016\u20132017}}</ref> in 2016 and ''[[Coldplay: A Head Full of Dreams]]'' in 2018.\n\n==Awards==\nFanning has been the recipient of a number of 'Best DJ' awards from various publications, including [[Hot Press]] where he topped the annual Readers' Poll for over twenty years. In 1980, he was the first person ever outside of [[RT\u00c9 Radio 1]] to be honoured with a prestigious [[Jacob's Awards|Jacob's Award]] for \"the depth and scope\" of his radio show. Following [[Christy Moore]] in 1990 and preceding [[Van Morrison]] in 1992, Fanning was awarded the [[Irish Recorded Music Association|IRMA]] Special Industry Award in 1991. In recent years he's been the recipient of a number of accolades and awards ranging from the 2012 [[Dublin Lord Mayor]]\u2019s Award (\"To the voice of Irish Radio, in recognition of his broadcasting career, his support of new Irish talent and for bringing alternative Irish music to an Irish audience\")<ref name=\"auto\"/> to the 2014 [[University College Dublin]] Music Society Award. (The Honorary Fellowship citation reads \"in recognition of his outstanding contribution to music through his work as a journalist, DJ and broadcaster \u2013 in particular his support of homegrown Irish talent\"). He won numerous IRMA awards and was nominated for Best DJ at The [[Meteor Music Awards]] on seven occasions, winning four times. U2 performed a special tribute when he won the Special Industry award in 2004. In 2016, he was inducted into the Irish Radio Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n{{awards table}}\n|-\n| [[2004 Meteor Awards|2004]] || Dave Fanning || Industry Award || {{won}}\n|-\n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{2fm}}\n{{RTER1}}\n{{U2}}\n{{You're a Star}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fanning, Dave}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Irish DJs]]\n[[Category:Irish film critics]]\n[[Category:Irish music journalists]]\n[[Category:Irish television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Jacob's Award winners]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 Radio 1 presenters]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 2fm presenters]]\n[[Category:RT\u00c9 television presenters]]\n[[Category:People educated at Blackrock College]]\n[[Category:Electronic dance music DJs]]\n", "name_user": "Jamesohal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eU2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dave_Fanning"}
